<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Man Killed In N. Ireland Bomb Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 25 (Xinhua) - A man was killed in a booby trap
car bomb-explosion at noon today on a loyalist housing estate in
Bangor, Northern Ireland, according to a report from Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The man was pulled out from his blazing vehicle with serious
leg injuries and died later in hospital, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It was not yet known what had caused the explosion but local
people said they thought it was a bomb.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said: "It would appear that he had been
driving the car when the explosion occurred. It is not believed
that anyone else was injured."
</P>
<P>
The anti-British guerrilla group, the Irish Republican Army,
declared a cease-fire in July which paved the way for the
all-party peace talks, but the hard-core "continuity IRA" faction
exploded a carbomb in a small rural town in September.
</P>
<P>
However, Northern Ireland Security Minister Adam Ingram
said there was some indication that the bombing was "not
sectarian". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
