<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Offocial Confirms Attempt for Co-Hosting National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong wish to host some
of the events on the competition program for the Ninth Chinese
National Games in 2001, a leading Hong Kong sports official
confirmed here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Fok, Head of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) delegation for the Eighth National Games which closed
in Shanghai on Friday, said that co-hosting the next national
games helps local sports community in their drive to further
sports development.
</P>
<P>
The 2001 games are to be held in Guangzhou, capital city of
South China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Fok said that Hong Kong SAR would have to bid officially for
the right to be the co-hosts with Guangzhou. "Anyway, we've
enough time to realize this as there are four years before the
games," he said.
</P>
<P>
The idea got positive response from Guangdong sports officials,
he said. "But we have to wait for the final words from the
central government," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fok, who is also President of the Hong Kong Football
Association, made these comments at a press conference at the
airport after the Hong Kong SAR delegation returned from Shanghai
today.
</P>
<P>
Fok praised HKSAR's athletes for their performance at the
national games, where they won one gold medal from the men's 180
kilometers individual road cycling race, plus the Olympic gold
medal won by Hong Kong's ace woman windsurfer Lee Lai Shan at last
year's Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
He said HKSAR's participation of the games, which took place
only three months after the establishmen of the SAR, was unique.
"This is a move of historical significance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fok also wished that HKSAR delegation's performacne at Shanghai
would help to win more governmental support and financial
investment into local sports.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Hong Kong Sports Development Board (SDB)
echoed the comments, saying that the establishment backs such
efforts.
</P>
<P>
"The SDB supports local sports assciations in their drive to
promote individual sports and would try to win more financial
support for them from the governmene, according to actual needs
and our financial capability," said Andrew Ma, SDB's Chief
Executive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
