<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-25 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russian Backs Land-for-Peace Formula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov arrived here before noon today from the Lebanese
capital Beirut in an effort to help solve the Mideast peace crisis.
</P>
<P>
On his arrival at Damascus International Airport, Primakov
told reporters that Russia insists on the continuation of the
Middle East peace process on the basis of the Madrid Conference
and the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Russia is a co-sponsor of the peace process, together with the
U.S., at the 1991 Madrid Conference. But it has mainly absent from
this arena over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Primakov pointed out that peace negotiations should not be
affected by the change of governments. Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu came to power last year and retreated from commitments
of the previous governments, including a withdrawal from the Golan
Heights it seized from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister said he will exchange views with
Syrian President Hafez Assad and Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa
on the stalled Middle East peace process as well as bilateral ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that Syria plays a key role in the Middle East
peace process and praised the ties of friendship and cooperation
between Russia and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's ongoing Mideast trip includes Lebanon, Syria, Israel
the Palestinian self-rule territories, Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He arrived here after a one-day visit to Lebanon where he met
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi and Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
