<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-25 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Stops Issuing Entry Visas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has stopped issuing
entry visas to foreigners as a security measure to the
Middle East and North Africa Economic Conference, the Qatari
news agency said today.
</P>
<P>
"The measure has been taken as a precautionary step to
boost security ahead of the conference, " the news agency
quoted an official in the Qatari Interior Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It has taken effect from October 20 and will be in
force till November 20. It applies to all nationalities," the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which has been downgraded from a summit to a
ministerial level under the pressure by some Arab countries'
boycott due to the Israeli participation, is scheduled to take
place in Doha on November 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
Qatar expected some 2,900 foreign participants from more than
90 countries and international organizations will take part in the
conference which is traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel
and their major partners in the other part of the world.
</P>
<P>
Qatari Foreign Ministry said that all major hotels in Doha
have been booked by the ministry and three floating hotels
have been ordered to accommodate the delegates during the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace
talks, Syria, Lebanon, the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia
have announced to boycott the annual conference, the fourth since
it was launch in 1994. And some other Arab states such as Egypt
have made it clear that they would participate in the conference
on condition of concrete progress in the Middle East peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
