<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, October 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Visiting Palestinian President Yasser Arafat today
called on the European Union (EU) to exert "constructive pressure"
on Israel so as to break the deadlock in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting here with German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel, Arafat said the failure of the Israeli government to
fulfill its commitments under peace agreements was the only reason
for the current deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is a strategic option not only for the Palestinian
people, but also for the Israeli people. It is a necessity for
the Arab world and the Middle East region. We must protect the
peace with all the possibilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that 70 percent of Israel's economy was linked to
Europe, Arafat called on the EU to use its economic clout to bring
pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We are calling for constructive pressure on Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said he will visit the
United States with a friendly attitude and with the hope for
increasing friendship between the two peoples, and expanding and
strengthening common ground between the two countries and their
friendly relations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang met with and answered questions from bureau chiefs of
U.S. media agencies on the eve of his state visit to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
There is no need for reticence concerning some differences
existing between the two countries, said Jiang, adding that common
ground can be sought and differences preserved through dialog.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that my forthcoming visit will fulfill the goal of
increasing understanding, expanding common understanding,
developing cooperation and jointly building up the future," said
the president.
</P>
<P>
He described the U.S. as the world's most developed capitalist
country and China a major developing power. "The three joint
communiques between the two countries are the basis for
Sino-U.S. relations." said Jiang, adding that "we should properly
and earnestly implement the communiques. We still have a great
deal of work to do in this regard."
</P>
<P>
"We sincerly hope to further promote Sino-U.S. relations on
this basis," according to the Chinese president.
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Sri Lankan security forces detained around 1,000
citizens in a track-down operation conducted in the capital city
of Colombo in early hours today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte in a statement
issued this evening said the operation was aimed at curbing the
threat posed to the capital, particular to the Tamil community, by
 the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
Police began to detain suspects after they cordoned the
city. By 8:00 am local time when the operation was concluded, a
total of around 1,000 people were under police custody.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Ex-military strong-man Denis Sassou Nguesso, the
winner of Congo Brazzaville's civil war in the past four months,
installed himself today as president after his return to the
capital, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 54, Sassou took the oath of office in the
People's Palace parliament building in the Congolese capital
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Greeted by about 1,500 followers, Sassou said that national
forums would be organized shortly in Brazzaville to decide on the
length of the transition and on a date for national elections in
Congo, an oil-producing former colony of France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
