<HEADLINE> UK Announces Initiatives on UK-Caribbean Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBURGH, October 25 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
announced a series of initiatives on promoting cooperation between
Britain, Europe and the Caribbean countries at the on-going
Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting (CHOGM).
</P>
<P>
During wide-ranging talks with delegates of the Carribean
Community (CARICOM) countries, British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook proposed convening a Region Forum "where all those with an
interest in the Caribbean can discuss practical measures to
address issues such as economic development and diversification,"
according to a British Foreign Office statement.
</P>
<P>
The Britain-Chaired Region Forum, which will meet early next
year, will also discuss issues on trade, tourism, investment,
drugs and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Cook also proposed that CARICOM create a Caribbean Investment
Bureau to promote investment between Britain and Caribbean
countries with the assistance of the Invest in Britain Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the British government appoints an informal
Advisory Group of prominent British figures, mainly of Carribean
origin, to advise British government ministers on promoting
broader relations with the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Cook said in the statement: "I am delighted that we were able
to reach agreement on these imaginative ideas to foster closer
links between Britain, Europe and the Caribbean states."
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the close ties between the people of
both regions, and our shared interests, will enable us to work
more closely in partnership for the benefit of all the Caribbean
countries and territories," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
