<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horror Bus Crash in S. Africa Shocks Govt, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 25 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government and political parties were shocked by a horror
collision between a bus and a petrol tanker in the Kwazulu-Natal
province that killed 33 women early this morning.
</P>
<P>
The women were burned to death when their bus collided with a
stationary fuel tanker near Mandini, a city more than 100
kilometers north of Durban, at about 4 a.m. (0200 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The bus burst into flames in impact of the collision and the
women were burned beyond recognition, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Ten other people were injured, one of them critically, in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
The women, members of the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) Women's
Brigade, were traveling from Port Shepstone in the south coast of
Kwazulu-Natal to the northern city of Ulundi for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
South African Acting President Thabo Mbeki learned with "shock
and disbelief" about the tragic accident, his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the government, the people of South Africa and
on my own behalf, I would like to convey our condolences to the
IFP, its president Inkosi (Mangosuthu) Buthelezi and the
next-of-kin," spokesman Thami Ntenteni said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the acting president had called on all road users to
take extra pre-cautionary measures and to drive safely
particularly as the festive was approaching.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents usually peak around the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
"It is tragedy that we are losing more and more of our beloved
ones through road accidents," he quoted Mbeki as saying.
</P>
<P>
The IFP reacted with shock at the accident.
</P>
<P>
IFP spokesman Hennie Bekker said: "We, in the IFP, pray that
the families and those injured will receive strength and courage
and that the sorrow and wounds may eventually heal."
</P>
<P>
IFP leader Buthelezi said he was "deeply shocked" at the news
of the accident, and expressed sincere sympathies to the injured
and the families of those killed.
</P>
<P>
He announced that a relief fund had been established for the
families of the 33 women killed in the accident and called for
donations.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal to the people of Kwazulu-Natal to give generously to
help pay for the funeral costs and to support the families who
have lost their mothers," Buthelezi said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said details of the fund would be made available on Monday
once the necessary formalities had been attended to.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the ruling African National Congress (ANC) Ronnie
Mamoepa said his party has learned with "shock and horror" of the
untimely death of 33 IFP Women's Brigade members.
</P>
<P>
"We share the pain and grief and suffering with those who lost
their loved ones in this accident," said Mamoepa.
</P>
<P>
He said the ANC policy-making National Executive Committee
expressed its heartfelt condolences to the bereaved families, and
wished those wounded a speedy recovery.
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa said the ANC extended its sympathies to IFP Women's
Brigade president, Faith Gaza, and IFP leader Buthelezi "on these
trying moments."
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party also extended its condolences to the
families and friends of those who died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
After the tragic crash, Transport Minister Mac Maharaj
announced a week of mourning for a total of 53 people killed in
road accidents in Kwazulu-Natal in the last six days.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, 11 people were killed in a crash between an
articulated truck and an open truck carrying laborers at Bulwer,
some 100 kilometers west of Durban.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, five people were killed in a collision between a
bus and a truck on the N2 highway between Port Shepstone and
Harding, a town about 60 kilometers west of the sea port.
</P>
<P>
Three other people were killed earlier today when two cars ran
into the back of a lorry on the N3 highway at Van Reenen, 250
kilometers northwest of Durban.
</P>
<P>
Provincial Transport Ministry spokesman Ranjeni Munusamy said
motorists were asked to switch on their head lights from Monday
until Friday as a sign of remembrance for those who died, and as
a commitment from the people of Kwazulu-Natal to road safety.
</P>
<P>
Munusamy said the Transport Department will appoint a
commission to investigate into the recent spate of collisions
involving heavy motor and passenger vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal's top transport official is seeking an urgent
meeting with freight industry officials in the province to
discuss the matter, Munusamy said.
</P>
<P>
An "Arrive Alive" campaign is underway in the country to
enhance road safety. Police set up numerous road blocks in major
cities to curb drunk driving and other forms of reckless road
behavior.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, road accidents are frequent owing to high
speed of vehicles, among other factors. In the country, few
drivers observe speed limits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
