<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Launches South Asia Regional Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBURGH, October 25 (Xinhua) -- A new Commonwealth regional
fund for South Asia was launched at the Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting (CHOGM) here this afternoon, which is designed
to help regional economic development.
</P>
<P>
The South Asia Regional Fund (SARF) is the third in a planned
series of regional investment funds established following the
Africa and Pacific funds under the umbrella of the Commonwealth
Private Investment Initiative (CPII).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony at the Edinburgh
International Convention Center, Commonwealth Secretary-General
Emeka Ayaoku said: "This fund constitutes yet another example of
the Commonwealth's unique capacity to promote cooperation and
foster economic development among its member states."
</P>
<P>
"The South Asia region is generating strong demand for
investment capital, driven by rapid economic growth and continuing
economic reforms. I am confident that SARF can make a significant
contribution to the development in South Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The SARF Fund, which covers the Commonwealth countries of
Bangladesh, India, the Maldives, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, as well as
non-Commonwealth members of Bhutan and Nepal, could finally reach
the volume of 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the SARF member countries, President
Maumoon Gayoom of Maldives said that regional fund can be very
effective in implementing the CPII program and it is a timely
contribution to the development process in the South Asian
Association for Regional Corperation (SAAR) countries.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the (SARF) fund can open up new
opportunities for the flow of foreign investment capital," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Commonwealth Development Corporation (CDC), which has
wide-ranging networks in the region, will be empowered to manage
the SARF Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
