<HEADLINE> Thousands of Black Women Rally in Philadelphia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of black women
from various parts of the United States gathered in the city of
Philadelphia today to join a Million Woman March to show their
solidarity and strength.
</P>
<P>
The women stood shoulder to shoulder for more than a
kilometer in the street in a rainy weather, local TV shows. The
morning march and a daylong rally was organized by two housing
activists who relied on a grass-roots approach to reach out to
black women.
</P>
<P>
The march started with a procession beginning at 7 a.m. near
the Liberty Bell, traveling three kilometers to a stage at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, the former wife of South Africa
President Nelson Mandela, was one of the speakers scheduled to
address the crowd during the daylong rally.
</P>
<P>
The rally echoes the Washington Million Man March in 1995, a
gathering of black men, and the Promise Keepers, a Christian men's
organization, earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Phile Chionesu, a co-founder of the march said, "The march is a
declaration of independence against ignorance, injustice, poverty
and abuse, and all the negative things that tend to separate us as
black women and deteriorate us as a people."
</P>
<P>
City officials estimated the gathering would attract 700,000
women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
