<HEADLINE> Trade Unions Urged to Help African Workers Live </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 25 (Xinhua) -- The Pan-African Workers
Conference has appealed to trade unions and workers to join hands
in improving the poor living conditions of workers.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference, ended over the weekend, has
criticized that trade unions across the continent have become
less representative of workers and agreed to take measures to
reverse the trend.
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting, with the theme of "Africa for Democratic
Participation," was attended by trade union and worker
representatives as well as academicians, government officials and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The conference has brought to the surface the poor living and
working conditions of African workers, their unfavroable
employment and income situation, and precarious trade union
situation in the generally unfavorable labor-management
relationship.
</P>
<P>
The participants in their resolutions also called on national
policy workshops on democratic participation to support
collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
On gender equality, they called for increased participation of
women in trade union structures and other decision making bodies
underscoring that the present percentage of women's involvement
was too small.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 25 countries said it is necessary to create
conditions for the Organization of African Trade Union Unity
(OATUU) to forge closer relationship with other international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
They also urge trade unions to strengthen cooperation with
universities and other civil organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
