<HEADLINE> Kuwait Welcomes UN Latest Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait today welcomed a
new resolution adopted by the U.N. Security Council which
threatens to impose new sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's State Minister for Cabinet Affairs and official
political spokesman Abdel Aziz Al-Dakheel told reporters that
resolution 1134 which was adopted Thursday night is a "proof
of the international legitimacy consensus and determination on
forcing Baghdad to implement international commitments."
</P>
<P>
The resolution sponsored jointly by the United States and
Britain warned of adopting new punitive measures against Iraq
and threatened to impose travel ban on all Iraqi officials
and military personnel responsible for hampering the task of
U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Three of the five permanent Security Council members China,
France and Russia abstained in the vote pushed through by
the U.S. and British delegations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been criticizing Iraq of continuing to hamper
the mission of U.N. weapon inspectors but Iraq said it did
not block their mission.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dhakheel said Kuwait was thankful to the countries which
voted in favor of the resolution against Iraq which occupied
Kuwait for seven months before its troops were driven out by
a U.S.-led allied armed forces during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that "Kuwait sympathizes with the suffering
of the Iraqi people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
