<HEADLINE> Jordan: No Deal with Israel on Palestinian Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today said that it would
not discuss with Israel any issue or project in the Jordan Rift Valley
that concerned the occupied Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Water and Irrigation Munther Haddadin made these
remarks while meeting with visiting Palestinian Minister of Civil
Affairs Jamil Tarifi, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel are currently considering to establish a
Red-Dead Canal which runs through the desert along the Red Sea to
the Dead Sea, semi-official paper Jordan Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Part of the occupied Palestinian territories lies on the
western side of the Jordanian-Israeli border which runs from the
southern tip of the Dead Sea to the northern tip of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting, both sides discussed water project
cooperation and the means to develop Jordan Rift Valley.
</P>
<P>
Haddadin affirmed Jordan's support for the Palestinians in the
field of water.
</P>
<P>
Neither of them disclosed details of their cooperation during
a press conference after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Jordan views the Red-Dead Canal project as the backbone for the
development of the whole Jordan Rift Valley region and the only
sustainable way to resolve its worsening water shortage, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The 190-kilometer canal, which is to cost at least 5 billion
U.S. dollars, is being designed to carry water from the Red Sea to
the Dead Sea, to generate hydro-electric power, to desalinate
water, to help overcome the problem of water shortage and to save the
Dead Sea from gradual evaporation.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan Rift Valley is the southern most part of the Jordan
River Valley which runs through the whole kingdom and is one of
the main water resources for the 4 million population of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
