<HEADLINE> Syrian President Meets Visiting Russian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Assad
met with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov here this
afternoon, with the presence of Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
Al-Shara, Damascus radio said.
</P>
<P>
The radio gave no further details of of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Primakov arrived here earlier today after wrapping up a one-day
visit to Lebanon as part of his Mideast tour to resume Russian
involvement in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Greeting Primakov at the airport, Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq Al-Shara lashed out at Turkey's building of a security belt
in northern Iraq, saying it would cause tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's plan (to set up the security belt) has no legitimacy
according to International Laws. Anything contrary to the
principles of International Laws and in violation of the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of states would of course
give rise to tension in the region," Shara said.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish newspaper had quoted an unidentified Turkish minister
as saying that Ankara has set up a fait accompli security zone in
northern Iraq by deploying 8,000 troops and will use it as a
starting point for military operations against the its outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party militants inside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
An Arab League official source had also denounced the Turkish
move, calling it an open violation of the sovereignty of an Arab
state which would but increase tension and violence in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian foreign minister told reporters that his country
agrees to Russia's joining in a panel monitoring the execution of
the "April Understanding" on the situation in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., France, Israel, Syria, Lebanon had come to an
understanding in April 1996 and set up a commission to monitor
ceasefire between Israel and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, a Russian entry should get the approval of all the
five member states of the commission. 
</P>
