<HEADLINE> Moscow, Grozny Call for International Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian and Chechen negotiators
have agreed to call an international conference on resolving the
relations between Moscow and Grozny, the Itar-Tass news agency
said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The conference could take place in Moscow, Russian Security
Council Secretary Ivan Rybkin and First Vice-Prime Minister
Movldai Udugov told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin believed that a conference involving leading Russian and
foreign experts could make the negotiating process between Russia
and Chechnya more transparent and guarantee its continuity.
</P>
<P>
Udugov said the talks have been difficult so far, because the
parties stand their ground on all issues, primarily the status of
Chechnya, and "it would be problematic to bring them to a common
denominator."
</P>
<P>
The report said that the negotiators of both countries mainly
discussed the implementation of previous economic and other
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Chechen officials complained the customs agreement signed by
Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin and Chechen president Aslan
Maskhadov has not been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin stressed the need to improve the work of the Russian and
Chechen governments to accelerate the implementation of bilateral
agreements.
</P>
<P>
On problem of hostages, Udugov said that the Chechen list
includes 1,438 people.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin noted that hundreds of people have been freed, but
hundreds more still remain in captivity.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission on a Moscow-Grozny treaty began its fifth
meeting on Friday. 
</P>
