<HEADLINE> U.S. Marines Flex Muscles in Bright Star Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Armored amphibious assault
vehicles speeded towards the beach, helicopter gunships boomed
overhead and transport helicopters churned up columns of dust and
disgorged scores of Marines.
</P>
<P>
This is the scenario on the first day of a week-long joint
combined maneuver involving air, navy and army forces from seven
countries in this year's "Bright Star 97" military exercises.
</P>
<P>
The coalition amphibious landing, carried out this morning on
the Egyptian Mediterranean beach, about 300 kilometers northwest
of Cairo, is the culmination of months of detailed planning
between the elite U.S. Marine Expeditionary Unit (MEU) and its
allies.
</P>
<P>
Poised off the coast on ships of the U.S. navy's sixth fleet,
forces of Egyptian, American and British, French and Italian units
combined to form a larger task force to carry out their
synchronized, rapid and unopposed build-up of forces ashore.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. 24th MEU spokesman 1st Lt Nat Fahy, this
coalition amphibious assault is the most sophisticated,
technologically advanced version of the amphibious assault as we
know today.
</P>
<P>
Although today's operation was technically an "unopposed
landing," which means "no live fire," it is a highly complex
operation that requires extensive coordination between the allies,
according to Col Richard F. Natonski, Commanding Officer of the
24th MEU.
</P>
<P>
"Once we herded men and machine onto slow-moving landing craft,
now we have replaced them with state-of-the-art equipment,"
Natonski said as he stepped down from a LVTP-7A1 armored
amphibious vehicle that has just reached seashore.
</P>
<P>
Despite wild speculations that the concept of the maneuvers
was based on Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, U.S. commander denied
that there is any "political implication" in it nor any third
parties were targeted.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there is anything to do with the Gulf War,"
though the MEU carried out such brilliant operations like "Desert
Shield" and "Desert Storm" in the 1991 Gulf War, said Lt. General
Tommy R. Franks, commanding general of the Third U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
No few than 58,000 troops from the combined forces of Britain,
Egypt, France, Italy, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates and the
U.S. will be taking part in the "Bright Star 97" maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian forces will account for roughly one third of the joint
troops while the U.S. brings with it the George Washington
aircraft carrier, the US Guam helicopter carrier, Apache
helicopters, Abrams tanks and 17,200 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The exercises started as early as 1981 and are being held once
every two years except in the 1991 Gulf War. They initially
involved merely Egypt and the U.S. until forces from other
countries began to join in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
