<HEADLINE> German Economy to See 2.4 Percent Growth This Year: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Germany's six leading economic
research institutes are expecting the country's economy to grow by
2.4 percent this year and 2.8 percent next year, the German news
magazine Der Spiegel reported today.
</P>
<P>
The latest projections, which will be formally published in the
joint Autumn economic report of the six independent institutes
next Tuesday, represent an upward revision of their Spring
projections of 2.25 percent growth for 1997 and 2.75 percent
growth for 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, they are still considerable lower than the forecast
made by German Chancellor Helmut Kohl last week that the economy
would expand by 2.7 to 2.8 percent in 1997 and would accelerate to
about three percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic growth, the institutes still see no
improvement on the job market. Instead, they are expecting a 1.3
percent drop in the number of jobs in Germany this year and a
stagnation next year, Der Spiegel reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, vice-chairman of the German Trade Union Federation
DGB, Ursula Engelen-Kefer, said today that Germany's unemployment
could climb further from the current level of about 4.5 million to
five million by February next year.
</P>
<P>
She threatened that if employers did not stop further job cuts,
trade unions would drop their current restraint at labour
negotiations and would demand more wage hikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
