<HEADLINE> U.S. Turns Back to It's Standard Time Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
return to its Standard time early Sunday and people will set their
clocks back one hour at 2 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
But residents of Arizona, Hawaii, the part of Indiana in the
Eastern time zone, Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands and American
Samoa will not necessarily change the time as they don't observe
daylight time.
</P>
<P>
Daylight saving time will return the first Sunday next April.
</P>
<P>
The nation has different time zones, with the East Standard
time clocking five hours behind the Greenwich mean time (GMT).
</P>
