<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola-Portugal Relations Enter New Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Angola and Portugal have
decided to strengthen their economic cooperation and promote it
to a new stage of development.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres' just ended visit.
</P>
<P>
He made his first visit as the prime minister to Angola at the
invitation of Angola's Prime Minister Franca Van-Dunem from
October 20 to 24.
</P>
<P>
The five-day visit of historical significance has brought the
friendly cooperation between the two countries to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between Angola and Portugal could be traced
back into ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Since the two ruling parties of Portugal, the Social party and
the Social Democratic Party, who assume power alternatively,
adopt changeable attitudes towards Angola's opposition party --
The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA),
bilateral relations between the two countries are not steady and
have not developed in accordance with the wishes of both sides.
</P>
<P>
However, things have changed in recent years. Since 1995, for
the first time in Portugal's political life, the Portuguese
government has adopted a clear attitude towards Angola's warring
factions and showed a very strong desire to develop cooperation
with Angola. It is under such circumstances that the exchanges of
visits by the two countries' leaders at high level have been
increased, with Portuguese leaders coming to visit Angola
frequently. They expressed their willingness to assist Angola and
at the same time to develop bilateral cooperation ties. Those
visits have paved the way for the development of the bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of 1996, the outgoing President of Portugal
Mario Soares first visited Angola, followed by incumbent
President Jorge Sampaio who headed a delegation to the country
soon after he was at the helm of the state.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, last April, Sampaio headed a government delegation
including the House Speaker Almeida Santos, Foreign Minister
Jaime Gama as well as many other government ministers to attend
the inauguration of Angola National Reconciliation Government. He
also delivered a warm speech on the occasion and reiterated his
strong desire to strengthen the bilateral relations and the
support to Angola's peace process.
</P>
<P>
This time the Portuguese government delegation led by Prime
Minister Guterres includes 64 entrepreneurs. The main objective
of the visit is to strengthen bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Guterres reiterated that it is not an
expedient measure to develop the bilateral relations but to make
it of long-term and strategic significance so that the two sides
could benefit from it.
</P>
<P>
Some 23 agreements were sealed to this effect and they cover
investment,industry, education, environment protection and other
aspects.
</P>
<P>
Just like what the prime minister commented at the signing
ceremonies that there is no longer any obstacles which could
hinder the development of the bilateral cooperation because it is
now built upon a solid base.
</P>
<P>
Portugal has a limited territory and lacks development
potentials. A large number of technical workers are jobless and
there is an urgent need to open up foreign market.
</P>
<P>
Angola has a vast territory, and is rich in mineral resources.
It has become Portugal's foremost target of foreign policy in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Portugal can get raw materials such as petroleum from Angola
and can also make a breakthrough for the development in the south
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Now with peace in Angola, the country needs to reconstruct
itself. It needs great technical assistance which could be
provided by Portugal. It will provide opportunities for
Portugal's extra technicians and is also good for Angola to
revive its economy.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation between the two countries will surely boost
each other's economy and further develop their bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Welcomes Russian Role in Mideast Peace: Assad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Assad
today told visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov that
Syria welcomes Russian role in salvaging the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Damascus radio this evening reported that Assad also urged
Russia to help seek a just and comprehensive solution to the
Middle East problem during his meeting with the Russian minister
with the presence of Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq Al-Shara.
</P>
<P>
Primakov arrived here earlier today after wrapping up a one-day
visit to Lebanon as part of his Mideast tour to resume Russian
involvement in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Assad assured the Russian official that Syria is willing to
continue the peace process, but it will only be ready to resume
peace talks with Israel from where they broke off.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister said that Russia, as one of the
two sponsors of the Middle East peace process, will try its best
to support the peace march and to seek a solution reflecting the
will of the international community and acceptable to all.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria and Israel broke off earler last
year. Syria insists that the resumption of negotiations depends
upon Israel's complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights on the
basis of 1967 borders as well as balanced and equal security
arrangements. Former Israeli Labor government informally agreed to
return the Golan Heights to Syria, but the current Likud-led
government does not recognize the promise. 
</P>
