<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Xiaolangdi Project Eases Fears of Flooding (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- With the beginning of
damming today of the Yellow River by a multi-purpose dam project,
hundreds of millions of residents in the river's lower reaches
will no longer have to live with the constant fear of flooding.
</P>
<P>
The principal aim of the Xiaolangdi Water Control Project,
second in size only to the Three Gorges Project in China, is to
control the devastating flooding which has plagued the Chinese
nation for centuries.
</P>
<P>
Of the drainage basin of the Yellow River, the second longest
waterway in China, 694,000 sq. km. or 93 percent is located
upstream of the Xiaolangdi site, a strategic position for flood
and sediment control.
</P>
<P>
Once operational, Xiaolangdi dam and reservoir, 40 km northwest
of the ancient city of Luoyang, will raise the flood prevention
capacity along the river from the current 60 years to 1,000 years
for the occurrence of major catastrophic flood.
</P>
<P>
Many hydraulic experts hold that construction of Xiaolangdi
Water Control Project has changed the long-held belief that the
Yellow River could not be tamed.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River has for years loomed perilously over cities at
elevations below the river bed, including Zhengzhou, capital of
Henan Province. Flooding in these areas would pose a serious
threat to all of northeast China and the Huanghe-Huaihe Plains.
</P>
<P>
Recorded history dating back 2,500 years shows that the river
has breached its banks on 1,500 separate occasions and the course
of the river has changed 26 times, resulting in high death tolls.
</P>
<P>
Wang Huaibao, a 90-year-old flood survivor, recalled a tragic
scene in 1938: "One day, when we were threshing wheat at a
grainyard, I heard someone shouting, 'the river bank has breached,
run!' People immediately climbed up to the top of houses and
trees. The water surged up and swallowed the whole village in
hours."
</P>
<P>
No large-scale flooding has occurred in the five decades since,
but Wang still climbs up to the top of the dam whenever it rains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
