<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Xiaolangdi Project Eases Fears of Flooding (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nevertheless, silting remains a serious problem, with
sedimentation raising the river bed in the lower reaches by some
10 cm per year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Yellow River, the world's muddiest
river, carries over 1.6 billion tons of sand annually, with each
cubic meter of water containing 35 kg of sand -- 69 times the
level in the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
After years of study, Chinese hydraulics experts have found a
solution: building a large reservoir between Sanmenxia and
Huayuankou. Xiaolangdi Village, located at the middle reach of
Yellow River and 130 km downstream of Sanmenxia, was chosen as the
site, where there could be the largest possible storage capacity
for a reservoir.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the flood control capacity of Xiaolangdi will be more
than all the existing 160 reservoirs along the Yellow River put
together.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and
the State Council have high hopes for and attach great importance
to the project. General Secretary Jiang Zemin of the CPC Central
Committee, and Premier Li Peng, have both inspected the
construction site several times.
</P>
<P>
The 40-billion yuan project will be of great benefit to the
people, said Zhang Jiyao, vice minister of water resources.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiurong, a 60-year-old villager, said she has been waiting
for the reservoir to be built since she got married in Xiaolangdi
at the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
The dam project has won support from the World Bank and other
international organizations. More than 10,000 workers, including
700 engineers from 50 countries and regions, are working day and
night at the dam area.
</P>
<P>
Olivier Collin, a German engineer, said, "The Yellow River is
of special significance to the Chinese people. I saw the revival
of an ancient nation at Xiaolangdi."
</P>
<P>
However, some hydraulic experts said that Yellow River
continues to be the toughest river to tame, and they expect their
descendants to harness it in a more scientific way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
