<HEADLINE> Sunan Canal Opens to Navigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Sunan Canal, the southern
stretch of Beijing-Hangzhou Canal, was opened to navigation today
upon completion of a harnessing project in east China's Jiangsu
province.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70,000 workers spent five years and two months to
complete the project, which involved a total investment topping
2.7 billion yuan (about 325 million U.S. dollars). About 8,945-mu
(about 596 hectares) of land was taken over for use and houses of
693,000 sq meters of housing were torn down. Forty-two bridges and
286 bank revetments have been built, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Beijing-Hangzhou Canal, the longest man-made canal in the world
and a symbol of China, boasts a bustling water transport operation.
</P>
<P>
The southern stretch of Beijing-Hangzhou Canal, about 208 km
long, flows southwards through Zhenjiang, Changzhou, Wuxi and
Suzhou cities in Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The navigation will help develop the economy of Jiangsu
Province and the Yangtze Delta.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Zou Jiahua attended today's opening ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
