<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Speakers on Poverty, Illiteracy, Overpopulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Speakers of South Asian
countries today called for overcoming poverty, illiteracy and
overpopulation in the region.
</P>
<P>
They noted that these problems had defied vast natural and
human resources, and deprived one fifth of humanity of fruits of
progress, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The speakers made their call at the second conference of
speakers and parliamentarians of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC), which opened here this morning and
is attended by delegates from India, Bangladesh, the Maldives, Sri
Lanka, Bhutan, Nepal and the host, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Speaker of National Assembly Illahi Bukhush Soomro
said that South Asia is the poorest part of the world.
</P>
<P>
In this region's countries, overpopulation, poverty, low
literacy and shortage of basic amenities are a big threat to the
social and economic order, he said.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the SAARC are peace, prosperity and people's
development, said Soomro. "We should work together to achieve
them."
</P>
<P>
P. A. Sangma, Speaker of India's Lok Sabha, said that South
Asia accounts for only 3.3 percent of the world's land surface but
its population of 1.2 billion is 20 percent of the world's
population.
</P>
<P>
"Our contribution to the world income is only 1.3 percent,"
said Sangma, "But we are the abode for nearly half of the world's
illiterate, and we have about 160 million malnourished children."
</P>
<P>
He identified alarming rate of population growth as a main
weakness of the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
"International trade is a proven strategy for economic growth,"
Sangma said. "We should concentrate in this area, keeping aside
our political differences for the moment."
</P>
<P>
Speaker of Bangladesh Parliament Humayun Rasheed Chaudhry in
his address also highlighted overpopulation as the main hurdle in
the way of progress.
</P>
<P>
He urged the parliamentarians to focus on tackling the issues
of overpopulation and poverty by addressing them at both
governmental and people's levels.
</P>
<P>
Dasho Kinzang Dorji, Speaker of Bhutan's National Assembly,
called for promoting economic cooperation among the SAARC member
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the Nepalese Parliament Ram Chandra Pudel called for
active role from all the member countries in combating the
problems in a concerted manner.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the conference, which will run
until October 28, will discuss ways to promote people's contact
among the member countries, and cooperation among the
parliamentary institutions of the member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
