<HEADLINE> TB, HIV Pose Threat to TB Control in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The pandemic of tuberculosis
(TB) and Human Immuno-deficiency Virus (HIV) is posing a serious
threat to TB control across South Asia as 40 percent of global TB
cases are recorded in this region with one million deaths per
year, experts said at a regional meeting which began here today.
</P>
<P>
They said there is clear evidence that HIV infection activates
TB in people with dormant TB by weakening their immune system and
that TB may speed up the progression to AIDS in HIV patients.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Health Minister Shanti Shamsher Rana stressed the need
to strengthen the training, supervision and education to produce
trained manpower at all levels and involve the community to
control TB while inaugurating the seventh Governing Board Meeting
of SAARC TB Center and the workshop relating to research on TB and
HIV in the SAARC member countries, Nepal's official RSS news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting and workshop are all board members of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) including
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
