<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Governments Urged to Act Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Governments in the Asian-Pacific
region should make political commitment and take visible action
against the spread of the human immuno-deficiency virus (HIV), a
senior U.N. health official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Peter Piot, executive director of the Joint United Nations
Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), was speaking to reporters on the
second day of the 4th International Meeting on AIDS in Asia and
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Piot said it is encouraging that the Association of Southeast
Asia Nations, particularly the Philippines, has promised to bring
the campaign against HIV/AIDS to its political agenda.
</P>
<P>
AIDS is the acquired immuno-deficiency syndrome caused by HIV,
which can be infected through sexual contact, injecting drug use
and blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
The spread of the deadly disease will cause serious
socio-economic impact in the region, including rising medical cost
and decreasing markets as a result of losing human resources, Piot
warned.
</P>
<P>
Taking Cambodia as an instance, Piot said that as one of the
poor countries in the world Cambodia will have to allot as much as
2.8 billion U.S. dollars in the anti-HIV/AIDS campaign by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Piot said governments should give priority to prevention in the
fight against HIV/AIDS, such as promotion of condom use.
</P>
<P>
Prevention is the most important way in checking the spread of
the epidemic and it is easy for governments to take prevention
measures against AIDS, which are "not highly expensive," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the five-day AIDS meeting earlier today, Piot
warned that the Asia-Pacific region, the world's most populous
region, is fast becoming a region with most HIV infections in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The number of estimated HIV infections doubled in the region
during the last three years to between 5 and 7 million, he said,
adding that it could easily double again by the end of this
century.
</P>
<P>
Among the Asian countries, India was thought to have the
largest population of between 3 and 5 million living with HIV,
according to Piot.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which discussed the current status of HIV/AIDS in
the Asia-Pacific region today, will focus on socio-economic issues
related to HIV/AIDS in the region and ways to curb the spread of
the disease in the next three days.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS, established in January 1996, is the leading
advocate for global action on HIV/AIDS. It brings together six
U.N. agencies in a common effort to fight the epidemic: the U.N.
Children's Fund, the U.N. Development Program, the U.N. Population
Fund, the U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization,
the World Health Organization and the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
