<HEADLINE> Qatari FM: 400 t0 600 Companies to Attend MENA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Qatari Foreign Minister has
said that 400 to 600 companies are expected to attend the Middle
East and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference scheduled for
next month in its capital Doha, the Qatari news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Sheik Hamad bin Jassim bin Jabri al Thani
made the remarks Saturday at the opening session of a meeting for
business executives on the Qatari private sector's role in the
MENA conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign participation in the November 16-18
conference would be larger than expected, adding that a large
number of countries, especially those from Europe, America and
Asia, would attend the conference at the ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
He did not mention any Arab countries, most of which have not
announced whether they would attend the conference, which would be
boycotted by some Arab countries due to an Israeli participation.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has sent invitations to more than 90 countries and
international organizations. The Qatari foreign minister said
that so far, more than 50 countries have signed up their
participation.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has downgraded the conference from a summit to the
ministerial level under the pressure by some Arab countries'
boycott.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace
talks, Syria, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates
have threatened to boycotted the conference.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon have not attended all the previous three
conference held in Casablanca, Amman and Cairo, in which Israel
took part.
</P>
<P>
The conference is traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel
and their major partners in the other parts of the world.
</P>
