<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU to Be Tough With Military Coups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, Ooctober 26 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim said coups
agaist democratically elected governments could not be accepted, and
the organization would be tough with military coups in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Sunday Mail in Harare yesterday,
Salim said it had to be accepted that mistakes were made by the
OAU during the 1960s because the organization then appeared to
accept coups as a way of life and regarded them as internal
problems.
</P>
<P>
''But now in Harare a decision was taken that coups against
democratically elected governments could not be accepted and that
the role of military in society was to guarantee territorial
national integrity and leave politics to popularly elected
governments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He regarded the OAU summit in Harare in June this
year as having been a turning point with regards to the
phenomenon of military coups against democratically elected
governments.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the message was getting home forcing
would-be coup-makers to understand that they would not be
welcome.
</P>
<P>
The military regimes, which declared that the civilian
governments had been corrupt, nepotistic and so forth, had
worsened the situation and never abandoned the corrupt practices
they accused the ousted governments of having been guilty of, the
OAU chief said.
</P>
<P>
On the just ended the OAU defence chiefs meeting, Salim said
the objective of the meeting is not to usurp the functions of the
U.N. because peacekeeping was enshrined in the U.N. Charter as
one of the international body's main functions. But, he said,
there are cases whereby the reaction of the U.N. is rather slow
and Africa is saying its people know their conditions better and
probably can react faster.
</P>
<P>
On democracy in Africa, Salim said the democratization process
in Africa is irreversible and that nobody, even those that are
inclined to dictatorship, could openly argue against democracy
because it is the people themselves who are demanding it and
will benefit during the process.
</P>
<P>
He noted democracy should be the logical outcome of ''our
people's struggle". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Maps Out Privatization Program for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Egypt plans to sell 15 public
sector trade firms and 35 hotel companies for public subscription
within the privatization program for next year, today's Egyptian
Gazette reported.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program for 1998 was approved Saturday at a
Ministerial Privatization Committee meeting chaired by Prime
Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it decided to add seven state-owned maritime
companies to the list of companies Egypt plans to privatize in
1997, thus raising the number of companies to be privatized in
1997 to 106.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif told reporters following
the meeting that the meeting reviewed an implementation program
for the 76 public sector companies whose shares were offered for
total or partial sale in the stock exchange in 1997, adding that
the government planned to sell the shares of 22 companies before
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting stressed that workers of a privatized company are
allowed to own up to 10 percent of the company's shares in
accordance with the employee stock ownership program, Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
The early approval of the 1998 plan for privatization means
that the holding companies should begin rectifying the financial
structures of their affiliated companies to be sold and settling
their debts so that they would attract potential investors, said
Ganzouri following the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The share of the private sector in Egypt's economic activities
has increased from 39 percent in early 1980s to 55 percent
in 1996-97, the government said in July. Meanwhile, the private
sector's contribution to the gross domestic product increased from
51 percent to 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
Egypt kicked off the privatization program to reduce government
involvement in the economy in 1991, but it has only got seriously
involved in privatization since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has promised to privatize more than 300 state-owned
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
