<HEADLINE> Training Class on World Heritage Held in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A 10-day training class on
the preservation of world heritage has concluded in Chengde, a
scenic and historical city in northern China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), the training class was
organized by the State Bureau of Relics (SBR) and the Chinese
National Commission (CNC) for UNESCO last month.
</P>
<P>
China has 16 world heritage sites, including the Mokao Grottos
in Dunhuang, the terra cotta warriors in the mausoleum of the
first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221-206 B.C.) and the Mountain
Resort in Chengde.
</P>
<P>
Yu Fuzeng, secretary general of the CNC, and Zhang Wenbing,
director of SBR, joined officials and experts from China and abroad
in discussing the preservation of world heritage.
</P>
<P>
During the training class, participants visited the Mountain
Resort in Chengde, about 200 kilometers northeast of Beijing, to
see the summer residence of imperial families in the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911). Visitors praised China's efforts in preserving the
resort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
