<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unicef Program Promises Poor Chinese Women a Well-off Future(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Six months ago, Peng Muying's
desire to start her own tailoring business was but a castle in the
air costing an unaffordable 1,000 yuan (120 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"I always dreamed of living a better life by running my own
tailoring shop, but 1,000 yuan is really a large sum for me and my
family," said the 18-year-old girl, who lives with her parents.
The four-member family earns about 2,600 annually.
</P>
<P>
To get her business off the ground, Peng got a loan from the
Social Development Program for Poor Areas (SPPA), an aid-the-poor
project initiated by the United Nations Children's Fund (Unicef)
in China. She now makes 300 yuan a month.
</P>
<P>
The micro-credit program grants each woman no more than 1,000
yuan to start small-scale business, like pig-raising or opening a
grocery, said Lin Fei, national program officer for SPPA.
</P>
<P>
The loan and the interest must be repaid within 14 months, she
said.
</P>
<P>
SPPA assistance has also been given to many of Peng's fellow
villagers in Luzhen, located over 100 kilometers from Hefei,
capital of Anhui Province in central China, since the spot was
chosen as a trial site for the SPPA program last year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half the residents of Luzhen earn less than 650 yuan
(about 80 US dollars) each year, most of them women.
</P>
<P>
Peng and 248 other women there received loans after completing
a six-month special skills training course.
</P>
<P>
"Unicef cares about the situation and is willing to help these
poor women and their children," Lin said. "But they should learn
some skills to help themselves, instead of simply getting some
relief fund and then spending it."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unicef Program Promises Poor Chinese Women a Well-off Future(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From the outset, the women discussed each others business plans
to ensure the ventures were practical and low-risk.
</P>
<P>
"I chose to open the tailoring shop because I like tailoring,
and more importantly, there is no such shop in our village," Peng
said.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of business, Peng, along with 248 other
women in Luzhen, who were put on the program, earned a total
profit of 181,000 yuan, or 700 yuan per person.
</P>
<P>
"It is the most effective poverty-relief method ever
implemented here. We should learn something from it, such as
strict management on loan providing and payment," said village
head Du Shizhong.
</P>
<P>
"The SPPA project can also help improve the education, health
care and hygiene conditions of those poor women and their
children," said Lin Fei. "Only when the quality of rural women is
improved can the root of poverty be removed. That's our ultimate
aim."
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation and local governments, Unicef is carrying out SPPA
program in 24 counties of 15 provinces and autonomous regions. It
plans to pledge a total of over seven million US dollars for the
work in China by the end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
