<HEADLINE> Knauss Leads in Opening of Men's Giant Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Hans Knauss of Austria made a
first-run lead of the opening men's giant slalom of the World Cup
season Sunday in Tignes, France.
</P>
<P>
Knauss clocked one minute and 09.10 seconds after he dropped
400 meters on a glacier more than 3,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Defending world champion Michael von Gruenigen of Switzerland
was second, timing 1:09.37, and his compatriot Steve Locher
finished third on 1:09.81.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Tomba, who has won two of the last three Olympic giant
slaloms, timed just 1:11.41.
</P>
<P>
He started 33rd due to his not having any point from last
season in the giant slalom. He competed in only two World Cup GS
races last season, skiing out in the first heat in one and not
qualifying for the second run in another. He also stopped in the
first run at the World Championship GS last February.
</P>
<P>
Luc Alphand of France, last year's overall champion, has
retired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
