<HEADLINE> Pak President Calls for Eradicating Poverty in S. Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari today called upon parliamentarians of South Asian
countries to play an effective role in addressing the issues of
poverty and illiteracy from the region which is home to one fifth
of humanity.
</P>
<P>
Leghari was speaking here this morning at the inaugural
ceremony of the second conference of speakers and parliamentarians
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC),
which is attended by delegates from Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
the Maldives, Nepal, Sri Lanka and the host, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the problems of poverty and illiteracy in the
region, Leghari said, "Without addressing ourselves to these
humbling facts, the pursuit of glory and prestige in any field can
only be a meaningless exercise."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot shut our eyes to the reality that despite the
incomparable richness of our cultural and civilizational
inheritance, our region has just about the world's poorest
economic, social and human development indices," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that political parties, legislatures and
parliamentarians of the region had an especially critical role to
play to address these problems.
</P>
<P>
"They shall have the task of formulating, debating and enacting
essential enabling legislation as well as developing the necessary
political perspectives which can enable us to resolve difficulties
that lie in our way," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Leghari stressed the need for strengthening the
structures of peace and development in the region.
</P>
<P>
"In its drive to maturity it is also expected that SAARC shall
evolve formal and informal forums and procedures for mutual
consultations that will strengthen the structures of peace and
development in our region," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the delegates to consider a range of specific measures
for the strengthening of parliamentary consultations and exchanges
in a number of technical, economical, social and ecological
fields.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Leghari said, "We need to collectively deliberate
upon broader trends in the world and in our region so as to ensure
that our policies towards each other and towards the world in
general are in conformity with the imperatives of the global
economy and the parameters of the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the conference, which will run
until October 28, will discuss ways and means to promote people's
contact among the member countries.
</P>
<P>
It will also discuss cooperation among the parliamentary
institutions of the member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
