<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Replace Expatriate Civil Servants with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is expected to
replace the foreigners now employed in its administrative agencies
with Kuwaitis from next July in a bid to reduce unemployment, a
Kuwaiti official was quoted today as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has decided to ban state administrative organs from
hiring foreigners as civil servants, local press today quoted
Walled Al-Wuhaib, general coordinator of the Civil Service
Commission, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners will no longer be allowed to get administrative
positions, unless they are extremely indispensable, by the end of
next June when their contracts expire, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 876,600 foreign laborers are currently working in Kuwait,
of whom 42,000 are employed in up to 10 percent of the positions
in state agencies.
</P>
<P>
Al-Wuhaib said that the commission has asked state agencies to
provide the list of the employed foreigners for it to take steps
to replace them with Kuwaitis.
</P>
<P>
He said that the lists are expected to be completed by the end
of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
