<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Trapped in Manila's Traffic Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- It is believed that everyone
living in Metro Manila has the experience of being trapped in the
unthinkable thickness of traffic either under the burning sun or
in heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, traffic jams have been part of the Filipinos' daily
life. To commute between home and office, some of them have to
spend three to four hours waiting in agonizing anxiety in the
paralyzed traffic.
</P>
<P>
Manila is rivaling Bangkok in terms of traffic mess and there
have been stories told about it: a traveler departing from Manila
airport arrives in Hong Kong before the people seeing him or her
off get back home; a businessman started driving home at 7 p.m. in
a heavy rain and reached his destination at 8 a.m. the next day;
and a commuter ran amuck and shot dead several people after being
caught in the traffic for a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
Believe them or not, traveling in Manila is becoming a both
mental and physical suffering. With an averaged car speed of 12
kilometers per hour, passengers are advised to restrain their
anger, try every means to be patient or take a quick nap before
the traffic flow moves again.
</P>
<P>
According to the local press, the traffic problem is now one of
the "bottlenecks" impeding the country's economic development,
causing an annual financial loss of 15 billion pesos (450 million
U.S. dollars). The amount represents the drain in money caused by
inefficient fuel consumption, unproductive man-hours, damaged car
parts and government investments to cope with the nasty problem.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the traffic mess is the result of a number of
problems, including inadequate infrastructure, inefficient
management, the poor traffic light system and lack of discipline
on the part of both drivers and passengers.
</P>
<P>
Manila now accommodates 1.6 million registered vehicles, about
65 percent of the country's total. In addition, nearly 3,000 new
cars are added to the already very crowded streets every month
while a huge number of dilapidated vehicles called "flying
coffins" are hanging on.
</P>
<P>
However, the capital city shares only 20 percent of the
country's road network. To aggravate the situation, the Philippine
government has spent only an average of three percent of its gross
national product on infrastructure in the past few years, much
lower than Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia and other countries in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The traffic light system also does not help the flow of
traffic. At most intersections, the drivers can see either an
outdated or defunct traffic light system or no lights at all. As a
result, they don't know whether to proceed or stop if no traffic
enforcers guide them.
</P>
<P>
The lack of discipline by the drivers and the commuters is also
making the traffic worse. In Metro Manila, a kind of passenger
vehicle called jeepney is sighted everywhere. To make more money,
most jeepney drivers like to race on the road, or stop wherever
they want, showing no courtesy at all to other road users.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most passengers do not like to go to regular
stations, they just stand in the middle of the road or other
improper places to wait for a jeepney.
</P>
<P>
First things first. Traffic authorities' inefficient management
is the most contributing factor to the traffic mess, experts said,
adding that it is too easy to get a driving license in the country
and that police are not very strict in implementing traffic rules
and some of them even take pretty bribes from traffic violators.
</P>
<P>
To ease the traffic chaos, the Metro Manila Development
Authority (MMDA) has tried many ways, but failed to improve the
situation. Its latest programs include the Unified Vehicle
Reduction Program (UVRP) and the Vehicular Occupancy Optimization
Scheme (VOOS).
</P>
<P>
Under the UVRP, vehicles are banned one day a week from all
roads between 7 a.m. and 7 p.m., depending on the last digit of
their plate number. The VOOS program stipulates that vehicles with
less than three occupants shall be restricted from using major
roads.
</P>
<P>
Facing protest from the masses, the MMDA has buried several
other drastic measures such as the express lane scheme and the
odd-even way which bans a vehicle three days a week.
</P>
<P>
These programs have reportedly reduced the traffic volume by 35
to 40 percent. But local people still don't feel the difference
and experts said the only way out is to curb the growth of private
cars and develop the public transport system.
</P>
<P>
Since September, people have found that Manila's traffic is
even worse than ever. The MMDA said this is due to several light
railway projects being constructed in the city. These projects
have occupied the inner lanes of some thoroughfares, thus
obstructing the flow of the traffic.
</P>
<P>
The MMDA said the traffic in Manila would remain the status quo
before these projects are completed in 2001. But will the
situation be largely improved after 2001? Experts said the only
answer is "wait and see."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
