<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Arrests 955 Illegal Expatriate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has arrested
a total of 955 illegal foreign laborers residing in the Kingdom
during the first five days of a campaign to clamp down on illegal
residents, a senior Saudi official said today.
</P>
<P>
Saudi director general of the Interior Ministry's passports
Assad Abdel Karim was quoted by the Saudi Press Agency as saying
that the arrests were made following a three-month amnesty
allowing the illegal residents to leave the country without any
punishment, which expired on October 17.
</P>
<P>
Saudi police and immigration officials have been raiding
businesses and housing blocks across the country in a crackdown
on illegal foreign workers in a bid to catch unlawful expatriate
laborers after the expiration of the grace period, Karim said.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners, mostly from India, southeast Asia and other poor
Arab countries, make up one third of Saudi population of 18
million population. No official figures of illegal foreign
residents in the kingdom are available, but independent sources
put the number at More than 500,000.
</P>
<P>
So far about 400,000 illegal residents have left the kingdom
for their home countries.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities announced in July a three-month period
allowing the illegal residents leave the country without
penalties and warned that those who did not leave the country
volunntarily in the period would face punishment of up to
100,000 Saudi Riyals (26,000 U.S. dollars) and a two-year
imprisonment to be followed by deportation.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Ministry warned people sheltering illegal
workers that they could also face jail terms of up to six months
and a 13,000 U.S. dollars fine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
