<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (3) II. Protection of Workers' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Labour Law promulgated in 1994 states that workers have
equal right to employment, the freedom to choose their jobs, and
the right to training, holidays and vacations, pay, labor safety,
health, social security, and welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
The government encourages people to find jobs through labor
departments or on their own by getting organized or forming
companies. To create more job opportunities, the government has
established many employment agencies and vocational training
centers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, there were 31,000 job agencies, 2,716
employment centers, and 200,000 service establishments which
provide nine million people with jobs. Labor departments' job
placement agencies helped 70 million people, 30 million of whom
were unemployed, in the 1983-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that, by September 1997, there were
about eight million unemployed, of whom six million had just been
laid off, putting the unemployment rate at around four percent.
</P>
<P>
To solve the unemployment problem, especially for people who
have been out of work for more than six months or who have
financial difficulties, China has developed a re-employment plan,
which has helped more than six million jobless people find work
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen thousand vocational schools provide training for more
than eight million students, and 4,467 technical schools enroll
700,000 people every year. More than a million people received
training in different types of programs in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Laws and regulations in 1995 reduced the 48-hour week to a
40-hour week, so that all workers get two days off each week. They
also enjoy national holidays with full pay. Women have a minimum
90-day maternity leave with pay, and people who live apart from
their parents or spouses are given vacations for family reunion
once a year.
</P>
<P>
China guarantees by law full pay for labor and equal pay for
equal work, regardless of sex, age, or race. State regulations
have set standards for the minimum of wages, and all provinces,
autonomous regions, and municipalities directly under the Central
Government have their own standards, with the exception of a few.
</P>
<P>
Workers' wages increase with economic development. Per capita
income for urban workers averaged 2,140 yuan in 1990 and 6,210
yuan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Laws and regulations also protect safety and hygiene in
factories, and deal with occupational hazards and safety in mines,
safety inspections and a supervisory system for the measures.
</P>
<P>
The laws and regulations have prompted enterprises to improve
working conditions and to create a safe and clean environment, and
China has increased spending on improved working condition. Twenty
million yuan is spent annually on labor protection technology, and
the number of injuries and deaths in Chinese factories have
continued to fall in recent few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A social security system provides workers with insurance for
retirement, illness, injuries in industrial accidents,
occupational hazards, unemployment or maternity leave.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, pension insurance had been introduced in
state and collective enterprises in urban areas, and 87.58 million
employees and 23.58 million retirees had joined the plan, and
103.2 billion yuan was paid out to pensioners in 1996.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the pensioners' livelihood, pension funds have been
established and their pensions have been revised upward to the
extent of 40-60 percent of the increases of their average wages in
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Medical expenses for serious illness are covered by a special
type of fund and the retirees' medical expenditures have
increased, and 7.91 million workers and 640,000 pensioners have
participated in the medical fund.
</P>
<P>
More than thirty million employees have taken out industrial
injury insurance policies in 24 provinces, autonomous regions, and
municipalities. The country now has 2,000 unemployment insurers
and 89 million employees are now covered by this type of
insurance, and 20.16 million people are covered by birth insurance.

III. Citizens' Right to Education and Culture
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic, the state has
developed education and culture through legislative and
administrative measures, using limited resources and calling on
all social strata to lend a hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Compulsory Education Law, Education Law, Teachers Law,
Adult Education Law, Higher Education Law, and Vocational
Education Law helped develop education through the legal system
and safeguard the people's right to education, thus forming a
sensible education system with numerous disciplines.
</P>
<P>
China spent a total of 226 billion yuan on education in 1996,
20 percent more than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Central Government and local governments allocated
121 billion yuan for education in their annual budgets, a 17.85
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The budgeted expenditures in 1996 accounted for 16.28 percent
of the government's total spending, 0.23 percentage points more
than in 1995, and education expenditures made up 2.4 percent of
the GDP, 0.03 percentage points higher than in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Illiteracy has continued to decline, as 2,078 counties and ten
provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities have reached the
objectives in their illiteracy campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Illiteracy is down to 6.1 percent among the young and
middle-aged people at present and it fell from 80 percent for the
entire population in 1949 to 12 percent in 1995, which represented
150 million people 15 years of age or older.
</P>
<P>
Nine-year compulsory education is now in effect in 52.2 percent
of the counties, and 98.81 percent of the school-age children can
get an education, whereas only 20 percent had that opportunity in
1949.
</P>
<P>
And, in 1996, 92.6 percent of those who finished primary school
could continue their study, up from 77.7 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, China had 1,032 colleges and universities, with 3.02
million students, and 1,138 colleges for adults, with 26.56 million
students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (8) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The country now has 162,000 graduate students working for a
master's or a doctoral degree.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China had 247 college students, 5,576 middle school
students, and 11,124 primary school pupils for every 100,000
people.
</P>
<P>
The women's right to education has improved dramatically. Over
90 percent of Chinese women were illiterate before 1949, but
several decades of work have eliminated illiteracy among 110
million women.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 98.63 percent of the school-age girls were in school,
and the gap between girls and boys in school was down to 0.35
percent from 2.9 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Women account for 27.6 percent of graduate students, 36.43
percent of undergraduates, and 45.29 percent of middle school
students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has 17,000 secondary vocational schools with 10.1 million
students. It also has 1,439 special education schools with 625,000
students and 610 vocational schools for the handicapped, providing
training for 274,000 handicapped people annually.
</P>
<P>
Since the policy for reform and opening began in the late
1970s, China has sent 250,000 people for further studies
abroad. Chinese also have the freedom to do scientific research
and literary and artistic work.
</P>
<P>
China's laws and regulations protect people's right to
culture. It has 2,202 newspapers and published 506,939 different
books from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, China had 1,239 radio stations, 880 television
stations, and a radio coverage of 84.2 percent of the total
population and TV coverage of 86.2 percent. Seventeen provincial
and municipal TV stations broadcast via satellite, and the number
of subscribers to cable TV had come to 50 million by 1996.
</P>
<P>
That year, 22 film studios produced 110 feature films and
distributed 174 new full-length films, 11 of which won awards at
international film festivals.
</P>
<P>
China's 2,689 art troupes put on 400,000 performances,
attracting 400 million people.
</P>
<P>
China has 2,641 public libraries, a 47-fold increase from 1949,
with a total collection of over 300 million volumes. The country
also has 32 exhibitions halls, 1,205 museums, 3,600 archives,
46,619 cultural centers, 374 people's art centers, 1,998 theaters
and cinemas, and 224 theatrical companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's cultural development is in response to increasing
demands for cultural life. Now both urban and rural people spend
more on education, culture, and entertainment. These accounted for
9.6 percent of per capita expenditures in 1996.
</P>
<P>
There are 102 color TV sets per 100 urban households on
average, and 87.97 per 100 rural households, 76.23 sets more than
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 640 million Chinese travelling in China,
spending 163.8 billion yuan on tourism.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, as a developing country limited by natural
conditions, China cannot avoid certain problems in promoting the
people's economic, social, and cultural rights. There are still
over 50 million Chinese without enough food and clothing. Many are
illiterate, and economic and cultural standards simply are not
high enough. There are still violations of human rights in social
life.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the task of the Chinese government and the people to
continue improving economic, social, and cultural rights still
lies in developing the economy, improving the system of democracy
and legality, and promoting socialist culture and ethics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
