<HEADLINE> Kenya Determined to Promote Cruise Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Ports Authority
(KPA) has launched a marketing strategy to promote cruise tourism
and about 17 luxury cruise liners are expected to call at the
Mombasa Port before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
KPA Managing Director Lenny Mwangola said in a press statement
issued this week that KPA was determined to promote the Mombasa
Port as a major and attractive cruise destination in the east
African region.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the first of the 17 vessels arrived at
Kilindini Harbor of the port this week where the cruise liner TSS
Albatros disembarked 172 tourists.
</P>
<P>
He said that the KPA would keep regular contacts with the
cruise liner owners and invite charterers to participate in
various international cruise conventions.
</P>
<P>
The port boss stated that the KPA had already invited cruise
line operators to undertake facility visits at the port and
spearheaded a campaign to sensitize the customs and immigration
departments on how to improve services to boost cruise tourism.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the KPA had formed a Cruise Ship Facilitation
Committee which was aimed at removing the obstacles hindering the
growth of cruise tourism.
</P>
<P>
The port chief executive pointed out that plans were under way
to form an Indian Ocean cruise association with membership from
13 member port states.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Mombasa Port handled 55 cruise ship calls with
18,000 tourists either embarking or disembarking at the port.
</P>
</TEXT>
