<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- China has tried for years to
give its people fuller economic, social and cultural rights, which
are an important part of human rights, according to Ren Yanshi in
an article released by Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has improved people's right to existence
and development in keeping with the realities in China, and
conditions in China have continued to turn for the better on the
whole.

I. People's Right to Existence and Development
</P>
<P>
This large country grew out of a semi-colonial, semi-feudal
society and, because of its large population, shortage of
resources, and relatively backward economic and cultural
conditions, the government made its primary task to safeguard
people's right to a decent life and well-being.
</P>
<P>
Since the People's Republic was founded, the government has
emphasized its obligation of feeding and clothing the
people. Relying on its own strength, China has generally solved
the problems of providing for its people, now 1.2 billion, an
historic achievement in safeguarding people's right to existence
and development.
</P>
<P>
With reforms and opening to the outside world, China has
stressed expanding the economy and building socialism with Chinese
characteristics, and augmented its productive forces. It rapidly
developed its economy from 8.8 percent annually in the 1979-1990
period to 12.2 percent in the 1991-1994 period.
</P>
<P>
By 1995, China had reached its 1980 goal of quadrupling the
GNP, five years ahead of schedule. In 1996, China's economy
continued to develop rapidly, with a GDP of 6.7 trillion yuan (816
billion US dollars), an increase of 9.7 percent over 1995 in real
terms.
</P>
<P>
Along with economic development, the Chinese people's standard
of living has risen. In 1996, per capita income of urban residents
was 4,377 yuan, three times that of 1978, when adjusted for
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income of rural people was 1,926 yuan in 1996, more
than four times that of 1978.
</P>
<P>
Bank deposits of both urban and rural residents amounted to 3.8
trillion yuan in 1996, a 182-fold increase over the 1978 figure,
and urban residents' savings deposits have now reached 45 trillion
yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Social and Cultural Rights for Chinese (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consumer goods have increased steadily. From 1952 to 1990, per
capita consumer spending rose 2.7-fold, reaching 3,919 yuan last
year, even though the population grew 98.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The quality of life has improved rapidly. Spending on food
decreased steadily, from 57.5 percent of total expenditures in
1978 to 48.6 percent last year in urban areas, and from 67.7
percent to 56.3 percent in rural villages.
</P>
<P>
Improvements can also be seen in living conditions, with per
capita floor space of housing in urban areas going from 3.6 sq.m
in 1978 to 8.5 sq.m. last year, and from 8.1 sq.m. in rural areas
to 21.7 sq.m.
</P>
<P>
Mary Robinson, the United Nations High Commissioner for Human
Rights, said in an interview this month that China has scored
remarkable achievements in education and in feeding and sheltering
its people in the past several decades and should be praised.
</P>
<P>
China has put a great deal of manpower, materiel, and funds
into getting rid of poverty. The number of the poor in rural areas
fell from 250 million in 1978 to 58 million last year.
</P>
<P>
It has also helped village people improve their well-being
faster. In the late 1970s, China had a fourth of the world's poor,
but now less than a fifth, and a target has been set of getting
all poor people out of poverty by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
With improvements in the people's standard of living and in
medical care, life expectancy has improved from 35 before the 1949
Liberation to 70-80 last year, and the mortality rate fell from 33
per thousand to 6.49 per thousand in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
