<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- More than 70 head of cattle
have been stolen by heavily-armed raiders believed to be from
Sudan in an attack in northern Kenya's Lokichoggio town, Kenya's
Sunday Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan police said the more-than-100 raiders struck the
area at around 9:00 a.m. local time on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
There was heavy fighting between the rustlers and Kenyan
police reservists before reinforcements from the Kenya Army, the
regular police and the paramilitary Government Service Unit
people were brought in, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the raiders defeated the
security forces and drove the animals across the border into
Sudan. No injuries were reported during the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Turkana District Officer Mahmoud Mohammed confirmed the
attack, saying the stolen animals belonged to traders who had
brought them to the town to await transport to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Security had been beefed up in the area to stop further
attack, he said. 
