<HEADLINE> Group to Co-ordinate Rare-earth Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A co-ordination group for
exports of rare-earth metal products has been set up to halt the
faltering momentum of international prices, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Made up of more than 50 major Chinese producers and exporters
of rare-earth metal products, the non-governmental organization
plans to prevent exports below a reasonable level.
</P>
<P>
The international rare-earth market depends heavily on Chinese
exports and the demand for Chinese rare-earth exports will grow
with the rapid development of high technology, said Yu Dahai,
director of the commodity department of the Chinese Chamber of
Commerce of Metal, Mineral and Chemical Importers and Exporters,
one of the initiators of the group.
</P>
<P>
Export prices should have gone up steadily, but, due to lack of
information, some Chinese rare-earth exporters sell their products
at comparatively low prices. This undermines the reasonable profit
margins of other producers and exporters.
</P>
<P>
Exporting rare-earth products at unreasonably low prices is not
only a waster of precious resources, but is also a burden on
generations to come, said Meng Guirong, president of the Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's largest rare-earth metal producer, with
its 1996 production of 45,300 tons accounting for 64.7 percent of
the world total.
</P>
<P>
Rare-earth is the name given to 17 chemically similar metals
with properties that are highly valued in industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
