<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU to Be Tough With Military Coups, Says OAU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, Ooctober 26 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Organisatio of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim said coups
agaist democratically elected governments could be accepted and
the organization will be tough with military coups in Africa.
</P>
<P>
have been a significant feature of African politics and he
regarded the OAU summit in Harare in June this year as having
been a turning point with regards to the phenomenon of military
coups against democratically elected governments.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Sunday Mail in Harare yesterday,
Salim said it had to be accepted that mistakes were made by the
OAU during the 1960s because the organisation then appeared to
accept coups as a way of life and regarded them as internal
problems.
</P>
<P>
''But now in Harare a decision was taken that coups against
democratically elected governments could not be accepted and that
the role of military in society was to guarantee territorial
national integrity and leave politics to popularly elected
governments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He regarded the OAU summit in Harare in June this
year as having been a turning point with regards to the
phenomenon of military coups against democratically elected
governments.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the message was getting home forcing
would-be coup-makers to understand that they would not be
welcome.
</P>
<P>
The military regimes, who declared that the civilian
governments had been corrupt, nepotistic and so forth, had
worsened the situation and never abandoned the corrupt practices
they accused the ousted governments to have been guilty of, the
OAU chief said.
</P>
<P>
On the just ended the OAU defence chiefs meeting, Salim said
the objective of the meeting is not to usurp the functions of the
U.N. because peacekeeping was enshrined in the U.N. Charter as
one of the international body's main functions. But, he said,
there are cases whereby the reaction of the U.N. is rather slow
and Africa is saying its people know their conditions better and
probably can react faster.
</P>
<P>
On democracy in Africa, Salim said the democratisation process
in Africa is irreversible and that nobody, even those that are
inclined to dictatorship, could openly argue against democracy
because it is the people themselves who are demanding it and
would benefit during the process.
</P>
<P>
He noted democracy should be the logical outcome of ''our
people's struggle". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Military Meeting Ends in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Chiefs of defense staff from
the members states of the Oganization of African Unity (OAU )
Central Organ ended a two-day meeting here yesterday evening.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed issues relating to command and control,
logistics, finance, communications, training, doctrine, structure
and operation planning for the OAU peace support operations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also provided a forum for the sharing of military
expertise, information and ideas in the search of strategies for
managing and resolving conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing session, Zimbabwe's Deputy Minister of
Foreign Affairs Nicholas Goche described the meeting as " a
milestone in the continued search for best ways and means to
prevent, manage and resolve conflicts that have ravaged the
African continent".
</P>
<P>
He noted that a collective approach is critical for the
realization and promotion of stability on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The gathering is " a clear and ample demonstration of our
common resolve and desire to assume greater responsibility for
tackling problems affecting Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, it constitutes a positive step in the
enhancement of our capacity building program as we aim to put in
place the necessary peace-support infrastructure," Goche said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to conflits in Africa, he said that Africa has been
plagued with serious problems whose root causes are poverty,
underdevelopment, ignorance and diseases.
</P>
<P>
He said that conflicts in the Great Lakes region, Sierra
Leone, Somalia, Burundi and Angola had shattered the economic and
social fabric of most of their societies and made the majority of
their populations the wretched of the earth.
</P>
<P>
The growing complexity of these conflicts and problems behoves
the OAU to strengthen its own mechanism for resolving these
problems, the Zimbabwean official said.
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore critical for the continent to sharpen its
skills in conflict prevention, management and resolution," said
Goche, adding that it is high time that OAU moves away from ad
hoc responses to crisis situations.
</P>
<P>
He called for African governments and people to harness all
available resources and experiences in order to seek solutions to
the challenges the continent is facing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
