<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiaolangdi Project Will Provide Flood Relief For North China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Damming of the Yellow River
for a huge water-control project begins today, and the project
will keep millions of Chinese living along the lower reaches of
the river from having to be threatened by floods again.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi Water Control Project, which is second in size
next only to the Three Gorges Project on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River, is intended to stop flooding on China's second
longest river, which has been known for a long time for the
disasters it caused.
</P>
<P>
The project will control 93 percent of the river's drainage
area and be able to handle large floods that may occur every
thousand years.
</P>
<P>
The river bed along the river's lower reaches is often more
than twenty meters higher than nearby cities, meaninng that, if
the river overflows its banks it could threaten Beijing and
Tianjin and would adversely affect the national economy.
</P>
<P>
For two millenia, the river has overflowed more than 1,500
times and changed its course in a major way 26 times. These have
affected several dynasties over the centuries, hence the saying
"While the Yellow River is calm, the society is stable".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Gold, Silver Prices Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 26 (Xinhua)-- India's gold price crashed by
115 rupees (3.19 US dollar) per 10 gm and silver declined by 230
rupees (6.39 dollar) per kg at the local bullion market Saturday
following reports that the Bank of Switzerland would be selling
about 1,400 metric tonnes of gold in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Gold, standard and ornaments, nosedived by 115 rupees at 4,350
and 4,200 rupees (120.83-116.67 dollars) per 10 gm respectively as
prices in overseas markets went down to 308.10 from 322.75 dollars
an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, gold was traded lowest at
4,370 rupees (121.39 dollars) per 10 gm on July 8. The gold prices
almost kept on losing in the domestic market after the government
relaxed the import control of gold.
</P>
<P>
Silver today lost 230 rupees at 6,730 rupees (186.94 dollars)
per kg as prices in the overseas market declined to the level of
4.88 from the 5.06 dollars an ounce. As a result, silver coins
also declined by 100 rupees (2.78 dollars) per 100 pieces.
</P>
</TEXT>
