<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiaolangdi Project Will Provide Flood Relief For North China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Huanbao, 90, is a survivor of the 1938 flood, when 800,000
people were killed. Standing on nearby high ground he saw with his
own eyes the entire process, where an entire village went under
water.
</P>
<P>
And, even though the river has not flooded seriously for the
past half century, Wang still has the habit of walking along it
when the high-water season comes.
</P>
<P>
The river bed in the lower reaches has been rising at an annual
rate of 10 cm and experts say that dykes can not prevent big
floods for good, but that the Xiaolangdi project, being built
where there is the largest concentration of floods, has a better
chance of stopping floods that the 160 existing reservoirs along
the river combined.
</P>
<P>
The project shows the wisdom and power of the Chinese and
belongs to both history and the present age, says Lin Xiushan, the
project's chief engineer.
</P>
<P>
The third generation of Communist Party leaders has shown great
concern for the project, and President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li
Peng have visited the project site several times.
</P>
<P>
Its cost is estimated at 40 billion yuan, and is helped by the
World Bank. Nearly 10,000 technicians and engineers from more than
50 countries and regions are taking part in the construction work.
</P>
<P>
One German engineer told Xinhua that the Yellow River is
important to the Chinese and that through the project one can see
an ancient nation reviving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
