<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children With HIV/AIDS to Reach One Million Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- More children are contracting
HIV than ever before, and there is no sign that the infection rate
is slowing down.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 1 million children worldwide will be living with
HIV by the end of 1997, according to the Joint United Nations
Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 400,000 children under 15 years became infected with
HIV worldwide, bringing the total number of children living with
the virus to 830,000.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 1.5 million people who died of AIDS last year,
350,000 were children, an UNAIDS report distributed during the
ongoing 4th International Congress on AIDS in Asia and Pacific
here said today.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, if the trend continues uncontained, AIDS may increase
infant mortality by as much as 75 percent, and result in an
increase in the under-five child mortality by more than 100
percent in regions most affected by the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS is the most recognized disease in the world today; but
the disastrous impact it is having on children has not been given
enough attention," said Dr Peter Piot, executive director of
UNAIDS.
</P>
<P>
Dr Piot warned that if the spread of HIV that causes AIDS is
not rapidly contained, progress already made by the public health
system in reducing infant and child death rates will be reversed.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
