<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Warns of Surging HIV Cases in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific is fast
becoming a region with most HIV infections in the world, with the
number of estimated infections having doubled in the last three
years to between 5 and 7 million, a senior U.N. health official
warned today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Peter Piot, the executive director of the Joint United
Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), issued the warning in a
keynote speech to about 2,500 delegates attending the 4th
International Meeting on AIDS in Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The HIV epidemic in the Asia-Pacific is accelerating faster
than anywhere in the world, Piot said, adding that one of the most
worrying aspect of the epidemic in the region was its trend.
</P>
<P>
The HIV is human immuno-deficiency virus that causes AIDS,
acquired immuno-deficiency syndrome.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures provided by the Western Pacific Regional Office
of the World Health Organization, Piot said the total number of
infections could easily double again by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Piot said India is the country
worst hit by HIV in both the region and the world, with its
estimated HIV-infected people reaching between 3 and 5 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
But in terms of percentage of a country's entire population,
Piot said, Cambodia and Thailand are the worst-stricken countries
in the region, with their infected people accounting for more than
two percent of their respective populations.
</P>
<P>
Piot said the most effective way of checking the spread of the
HIV epidemic is prevention so as to keep low-level infection
rates, citing the efforts of Singapore, the Philippines, and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Piot also praised the just-ended satellite symposium on AIDS,
children and youth in the Asia-Pacific, for its role in mobilizing
children and youth to take part in the campaign against the deadly
disease.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was held between October 23 and 25 in Manila as
part of the program of the current four-day AIDS international
meeting, which opened here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The conference will discuss, among other things, the current
status of HIV/AIDS in the Asia-Pacific, socio-economic issues
related to HIV/AIDS in the region, and ways to curb the spread of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
In parallel to the meeting, a grand exhibition will be held to
display publications about AIDS, medicines against AIDS and
efforts made by all countries against the lethal disease.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS, established in January 1996, is the leading
advocate for global action on HIV/AIDS. It brings together six
U.N. agencies in a common effort to fight the epidemic: the U.N.
Children's Fund, the U.N. Development Program, the U.N. Population
Fund, the U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization,
the World Health Organization and the World Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
