<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Waste Management Proposal Awaits Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A proposal for an integrated
waste management program in the Bangladeshi capital Dhaka has been
submitted to the government recently by a London-based private
firm, Pan Asia Services Ltd. (PAS), the national news agency BSS
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The program, to be implemented in phases and on the
Build-Operate- Transfer (BOT) basis, will require a direct foreign
investment of 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project will comply with the international human health and
environment standard, BSS quoted PAS Chairman Ghulam Murshed as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The PAS was optimistic about getting government approval, and
hoped to start a techno-economic feasibility study by the
beginning of next year. The study is expected to be completed in
three months, BSS said.
</P>
<P>
The major components of the project are collection and disposal
of wastes, four street cleaning units, transfer, sorting and
treatment centers, two landfill centers, one waste to energy
plant, one plastic recycling plant and a transport unit, the PAS
chief said.
</P>
<P>
The PAS chief said plastic bags will be supplied to households,
containers, hoppers and dustbins will be installed at the
collection points, and special containers will be provided for
toxic and hazardous wastes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 400,000 tons of untreated household and non-sortable
industrial waste will be transferred annually, about 40 percent of
which will be sorted out, packaged and sent to treatment
facilities while some portion will be baled or crushed, according
to the PAS chief.
</P>
<P>
The authorized capacity of each land-fill station will be
120,000 tons per year and each will fill 10 hectares, he said,
adding that to recover the excess heat of the exhaust steam from
power plants, the proposal suggests the setting up of a distilled
water production plant with a capacity of 100,000 liters per day.
</P>
<P>
A proposed composting plant under the project will have an
annual production capacity of 100,000 tons of quality organic
fertilizer, and the transport depot of the project will have 400
trucks, 80 modern waste tippers, street cleaning equipment and
personnel vehicles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
