<HEADLINE> Aid Group Meeting to Review Dhaka's Reforms Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Aid Group Meeting for
Bangladesh, to be held here early next month, is likely to review
Dhaka's reform programs in the banking and financial sectors and
progress in privatization, according to a World Bank report on the
meeting agenda.
</P>
<P>
The donors will also evaluate Dhaka's performance in other
agreed fields like the macroeconomic situation and reforms of
various public institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Aid Group's Dhaka meeting is scheduled for November 4-5
against the backdrop of a declining international aid climate and
donors' concern over a deteriorating political climate in
Bangladesh, said the report published here today.
</P>
<P>
But the most striking feature of this year's meeting would be
donors' in-depth review of the country's on-going poverty
alleviation programs.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank referred to inadequacy of the poverty
alleviation programs and said it was currently preparing a rural
development strategy that primarily aims to fight poverty at the
grass-roots level.
</P>
<P>
The slow pace of implementation of the aid-funded projects and
bottlenecks of aid utilization would also be discussed, as well as
infrastructural difficulties and the prospects of private
investments in this sector, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
