<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devaluation of Currencies Hits Indian Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 26 (Xinhua)-- The recent spate of
devaluation of currencies in Pakistan and some ASEAN nations is
expected to hit Indian exports of rice, soybean products and oil
extractions, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The sharp devaluation in the Thai Baht and the Pakistani Rupee
will make the exports of these countries' goods cheaper than
India's.
</P>
<P>
As India is directly competing with these countries in the
export of rice, soybean products and oil extractions, this is
bound to have an adverse impact on India's exports.
</P>
<P>
The spate of devaluation has come at a time when countries like
the Philippines were reeling under the EL Nino weather phenomenon,
which has caused a sharp decline in food production.
</P>
<P>
Under normal conditions, India could have taken advantage of
such a situation in pushing up its exports of agricultural goods,
but the devaluation of currencies by its competitors will now pose
a major hurdle.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, Indian rice exports already registered a 20
percent decline between April and July this year compared to the
previous corresponding period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
