<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Attaches Importance to Central European Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 25 (Xinhua) -- The Central European Initiative
(CEI) has a key role to play in preparing central Europe and the
Balkans for integration into the European institutions, Italian
Foreign Undersecretary Piero Fassino said in Triste today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting of parliamentary speakers from
the CEI's 16 member countries, according to reports from the city.
</P>
<P>
"The CEI can play an important role in holding together those
countries that, although close to entering the European Union and
NATO, sometimes feel these goals are still some way off," he said.
</P>
<P>
There were a number of ways in which the initiative could help
avoid new divisions or feelings of exclusion that the enlargement
of these institutions might otherwise bring, he added.
</P>
<P>
An awareness of the CEI's potential for knitting its members
into Europe ahead of formal membership of the EU and NATO had led
Italy to seek new ways to strengthen the initiative from within,
Fassino said.
</P>
<P>
"Central Europe and the Balkans are of the highest strategic
importance to Italy," Fassino stressed. The region's geopolitical
proximity, its solid political relations with Rome and its growing
economic and cultural ties meant that Italy looked with keen
interest at "this vast area extending from the Baltic to the Black
Sea and the Adriatic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
