<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Key Events in Sino-US Relations (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The following is a list of the
key events in Sino-US relations from 1971 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
April, 1971: The American Ping-Pong Team was invited to visit
China. The Chinese Ping-Pong Team paid a visit to the United
States in 1972.
</P>
<P>
July, 1971: Henry Kissinger, Assistant to the President of the
United States for National Security Affairs, paid his first visit
to China.
</P>
<P>
February, 1972: US President Richard Nixon paid an official
visit to China. The Shanghai Communique was jointly issued by
China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
December, 1975: US President Gerald Ford visited China.
</P>
<P>
December 16, 1978: A joint communique was issued by China and
the United States, announcing the formal establishment of
diplomatic relations between the two countries on January 1, 1979.
</P>
<P>
January, 1979: Deng Xiaoping paid an official visit to the
United States. An agreement on cooperation in science and
technology and a cultural agreement were signed between the two
countries during the visit.
</P>
<P>
1979: The Sino-US Joint Economic Committee and the Sino-US
Joint Committee on Cooperation in Science and Technology were set
up. The Committees have generally met on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
July 7, 1979: The Sino-US Agreement on Trade Relations was
signed between the Chinese and US Governments in Washington.
</P>
<P>
June, 1981: The Sino-US Joint Committee on Commerce and Trade
was set up which has generally met on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
August, 1982: A joint communique was issued on August 17
between China and the United States concerning the American sale
of weapons to Taiwan. The communique is thus referred to as the
August 17 Communique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Key Events in Sino-US Relations (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
March, 1983: Speaker of the US House of Representatives O'Neill
visited China.
</P>
<P>
April, 1984: US President Ronald Reagon visited China.
</P>
<P>
July, 1985: Chinese President Li Xiannian visited the United
States.
</P>
<P>
February, 1989: US President George Bush paid a working visit
to China.
</P>
<P>
May, 1989: Wan Li, Chairman of the Standing Committee of
China's National People's Congress, visited the United States.
</P>
<P>
December, 1989: Brent Scowcroft, Assistant to the President of
the United States for National Security Affairs and special envoy
of the president, visited China.
</P>
<P>
January, 1992: Chinese Premier Li Peng met US President George
Bush while attending a UN meeting in New York.
</P>
<P>
November, 1993: Chinese President Jiang Zemin met US President
Bill Clinton during the informal APEC leadership meeting in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
End of 1993: The Chinese Government found the remains of the
crew of an American military plane which crashed in Tibet, China,
during World War II and returned them to the US Government.
</P>
<P>
November, 1994: President Jiang Zemin met President Bill
Clinton while attending the informal APEC leadership meeting in
Bogor.
</P>
<P>
October, 1995: President Jiang Zemin met President Bill Clinton
while attending the special conference commemorating the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
October, 1996: The Chinese Government found the remains of the
crew of an American military plane which crashed in Guangxi,
China, during World War II and returned them to the US Government.
</P>
<P>
November, 1996: President Jiang Zemin met President Bill
Clinton while attending the informal APEC leadership meeting in
Manila.
</P>
<P>
March, 1997: The newly appointed US Secretary of State Albright
visited China.
</P>
<P>
April, 1997: US Vice President Gore visited China.
</P>
<P>
April, 1997: Speaker of the US House of Representatives
Gingrich visited China.
</P>
<P>
April, 1997: Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen visited the United States during which he met President
Clinton and Secretary of State Albright.  
</P>
</TEXT>
