<HEADLINE> New Suggestions Made for Cleaner Kathmandu Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Various suggestions including
construction of toilets in public places have come up for
improving the environment of the Kathmandu Valley in preparation
for "Visit Nepal Year '98," Nepali newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Toilets are not seen in public places in Nepal, and people just
urinate in the streets.
</P>
<P>
Other suggestions made at a national seminar include
controlling stray dogs, imposing a ban on selling and distribution
of illegally produced alcoholic drinks and implementation of
integrated environment preservation programs through coordination
among the three cities in the Valley -- Kathmandu, Lalitpur and
Bhaktapur.
</P>
<P>
The seminar also underlined the need to make necessary
arrangements for slaughter houses, renovate and conserve ancient
shrines and temples, improve the transport sector for
environmental protection and provide every household with dustbins
for collection of garbage.
</P>
<P>
Kathmandu Mayor Keshav Sthapit said that as part of its efforts
to make "Visit Nepal Year '98" a success, the city has intensified
garbage collection at night and has already killed some 14,000
stray dogs.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly organized by Nepal's National Zoonosis
and Food Hygiene Research Center and the Canada-based
International Development Research Center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
