<HEADLINE> Pivotals Suffer Major Setback on BSE Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Pivotals on the Bombay Stock
Exchange (BSE) market last week suffered a major setback with the
sensitive index sharply down by over 148 points in the wake of
sustained and heavy bull liquidation and scattered selling by
foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index, firm at 4,154.84 on Monday, later
gradually moved downwards to close the week below the 4,000
psychological barrier at 3,957.46 as against last weekend's close
of 4,106.26, showing a fall of 148.80 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index also dropped sharply by 65.05 points to end
the week at 1,703.43 from the previous weekend close of 1768.48.
The BSE-200 and the US dollar index were quoted substantially down
at 382.03 and 175.41 at the weekend compared with last weekend
close of 395.24 and 181.78 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bull operators, who had built up long positions in the past one
week, lightened their commitments fearing a major political
fall-out of the rejection of the Union Cabinet recommendation for
Central Rule in Uttar Pradesh by President K.R.Narayanan.
</P>
<P>
They were not willing to take any risk by getting delivery of
shares due to the political instability in the country. The lack
of interest was also attributed to the long "Diwali" (Light
festival) holidays beginning from October 28.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
