<HEADLINE> Million Women March Held in Philadelphia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Millions of black women from
various parts of the United States gathered in Philadelphia today
for the Million Woman March to show their solidarity in the black
community and their strength in the society.
</P>
<P>
Local TV shows that the women standing shoulder to shoulder
for more than one kilometer in the street in a rainy weather. They
started with a morning march and gathered for a day long rally,
singing the Black National Anthem and listening to speeches
encouraging them to show their power.
</P>
<P>
They came by train, car, plane and hundreds of buses to the
rally. The organizers estimated two million people filled the avenue
in early afternoon, and local police estimated the
participants at 300,000 to one million.
</P>
<P>
Called by two housing activists who relied on a grass-roots
approach to reach out to black women, the march started with a
procession beginning at 7 a.m. near the Liberty Bell and traveling
three kilometers to a stage at the Philadelphia Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
The rally echoes the Washington Million Man March in 1995, a
gathering of black men, and the rally of the Promise Keepers, a
Christian men's organization, earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The women's march was intended to show unity in the face of
inner-city problems ranging from inadequate health care and poor
education to high unemployment and crime.
</P>
<P>
Phile Chionesu, a co-founder of the march said, "The march is a
declaration of independence against ignorance, injustice, poverty
and abuse, and all the negative things that tend to separate us as
black women and deteriorate us as a people."
</P>
<P>
"Black women have been the epitome of strength in this
country," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We want to prepare our women, no matter what their status in
life, to look at how we can begin to invest as black women and how
we can begin to vote in blocs as black women." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: President Jiang Zemin on Sino-US Relations (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that though bilateral relations have undergone
vicissitudes in the past three years, the overall trend is toward
improvement, especially in the last six months, during which
increased high-level visits have solved some of the problems which
at a time troubled the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"I should say that bilateral relations have seen obvious
improvement," the Chinese president said. "And favorable factors
in the development of bilateral ties are increasing."
</P>
<P>
The two countries "now stand an advantageous chance in
improving the relations between them," Jiang observed.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1997, US Vice-President Al Gore and
other senior officials and statesmen have visited China.
</P>
<P>
During Jiang's meetings with these US visitors, he stated the
anticipation of his upcoming state visit to the United States and
the future of Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting with Gore, Jiang said that healthy and stable
Sino-US relations toward the 21st century should be based on three
principles: adherence to common interest, farsightedness, and a
proper handling of the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
On the adherence to common interest, he said that in the new
situation, the need for the two countries to maintain and expand
cooperation is not dwindling, but growing continuously, and that
in particular, there exist very great, cooperative potentials for
the two countries to jointly safeguard global and regional peace,
develop bilateral economic and trade ties, and promote the growth
and prosperity of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Governments of the two countries and their leaders should have
a full understanding about this. And what's more, people of both
countries should reach such a consensus, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On farsightedness, he said, "We should dispel all interferences
and noises in bilateral relations, stand higher and see farther,
get a firm hold of the fundamental interest of the people of the
two countries, and keep in mind the overall situation of bilateral
relations, the whole world situation as well as the endeavor to
bring into the 21st century a prosperous, stable and peaceful
world."
</P>
<P>
He said that differences on some issues can be resolved on the
basis of mutual respect, non-interference in each other's internal
affairs, and equal consultations. And if some differences can not
be resolved for the time being, the two sides can seek common
ground while reserving differences, but they can not meddle in the
overall situation in developing relations between the two
countries, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
