<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: President Jiang Zemin on Sino-US Relations (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With regard to the proper handling of the Taiwan issue, Jiang
said that the kernel content of the three Sino-US joint
communiques is precisely one that defines the guiding principle
for dealing with the issue.
</P>
<P>
The United States had made solemn commitment on the Taiwan
question. But in the history of the development of Sino-US
relations, the issue has experienced repeated hindrances, which
even undermined the process of improving and developing Sino-US
relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have talked about the topic time and again, just in a hope
that it would not affect the smooth growth of Sino-US ties any
more," Jiang stated.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang, in a meeting with Samuel R. Berger, assistant
to the US President for National Security Affairs, on August 12,
described the general atmosphere of Sino-US relations as good.
</P>
<P>
"Since my meeting with President Clinton in Manila last
November, relations between the two countries have had positive
progress, with common ground in many fields," he said. "This
situation is the result of joint efforts made by the two sides. It
has been painstakingly achieved and should be treasured."
</P>
<P>
He said that he is looking forward to discussing significant
issues about developing Sino-US relations with President Clinton
and joining hands with him to bring a long-term, stable and
healthy relationship of cooperation to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Due to their different social systems, ideologies, cultural
traditions, historical backgrounds, and levels of development and
also because they are both large countries with different
principles in handling things, it is natural that there are
disagreements between the two, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In properly dealing with these disagreements, Jiang said, the
first thing is to deepen mutual understanding. In doing so,
direct, face-to-face dialogues and exchanges between the two
countries' leaders are especially important. These contacts can
not be replaced by any other modern means of communication.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the importance of the two sides sticking to the
principles of mutual respect, non-interference in each other's
internal affairs, and equality in consultations. "We should ascend
the heights and be farsighted, and proceed from a strategic level
in mastering the general situation of relations between the two
countries, and strive to expand common ground, enhance trust,
diminish differences, and join hands to create the future."
</P>
</TEXT>
