<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: President Jiang Zemin on Sino-US Relations (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang, meeting with US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin on
September 26, said again that he expects to discuss with President
Clinton a wide range of issues including Sino-US relations and the
international situation during his US trip.
</P>
<P>
He said that he and Clinton will jointly set the guidelines for
Sino-US relations for the 21st century to raise bilateral
relations to a sound and stable period of development, based on
the principles of the three Sino-US joint communiques. "This is in
the fundamental interest of the two peoples, and beneficial to
world peace, stability and development."
</P>
<P>
President Jiang met with US Commerce Secretary William Daley on
October 8, when he said that great progress has been made in
bilateral relationship over the past year, especially in economic
and trade cooperation. "The two countries should continue their
efforts to ensure a long-term and stable development of bilateral
economic and trade relations."
</P>
<P>
He noted that China and the United States share extensive
common interest and have enormous cooperation potential in
safeguarding regional and world peace, and in furthering
cooperation in such sectors as economy, trade, culture, science,
technology and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed the hope that governments and leaders of both
countries will take a broad and long-term view, take the overall
situation into consideration and work together to bring a healthy,
stable and ever-growing Sino-US relationship to the next century.
 
</P>
