<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Threatened by Increasing Landslides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 25 (Xinhua) -- Italy, with 70 percent of its
territory being hilly areas, is increasingly threatened by
landslides, the Department of Civil Protection reported today.
</P>
<P>
Landslides have always been a problem for the country since
1945, which cause an average of seven deaths every month, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Umbria in central Italy has been identified as the region most
at risk potentially, followed by Liguria and Abruzzo, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Naples, a city worst affected by landslides, has been subject
to 93 landslides since 1945, followed by Genoa with 73 landslides
and Orvieto with 63 landslides.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said the increase in landslides is caused by an
irregular weather, deforestation, a declined vegetation coverage
and soil erosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
