<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: President Jiang Zemin on Sino-US Relations (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Since Chinese President Jiang
Zemin put forward a four-point principle guiding the development
of relations with the United States in late 1992, he has asked, on
many occasions, including the four meetings with President Bill
Clinton, leaders of both countries to treat Sino-US relations from
a strategic point of view to ensure the growth of such relations.
</P>
<P>
The principle Jiang put forward is: increase mutual trust,
diminish troubles, promote cooperation, and prevent confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is scheduled to leave here for the United States
today. Jiang and Clinton will meet for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
In November 1993, Jiang held formal talks with President
Clinton at the APEC informal meetings of leaders in Seattle. It
was the first formal meeting between top leaders of the two
countries since February 1989. The meeting was "positive,
constructive and fruitful," and marked a good beginning of such
talks.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed that both China and the United States are
countries of influence in the world and share common interest on
many important issues. To increase mutual trust between China and
the United States they can play a positive part in the world. It
is a reality that there exist differences between China and the
United States. The differences should be resolved through frank
dialogues on the basis of equality and mutual respect. Any action
of imposing one's own view on others should not be taken.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told President Clinton: "there are over a thousand
nationalities, more than 200 countries, many kinds of cultural
tradition and ideology on our earth. The right of people in
different countries to choose their own social system and
development mode should be respected. The diversity of the world
is a good thing, not a bad one. Different countries, cultures can
exchange with and learn from each other and share the fruits of
human civilization."
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that the Sino-US summit itself is
significant. The talks increased mutual understanding and will
help improve and develop Sino-US relations. The talks mark a new
beginning of Sino-US relations, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
After the Seattle meeting of Jiang and Clinton, Sino-US
relations showed a new momentum of improvement and development. A
year later, Jiang and Clinton met again at the Jakarta meeting of
APEC, exchanging views extensively with each other on the
international and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: President Jiang Zemin on Sino-US Relations (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the meeting, Jiang proposed five principles guiding the
development of Sino-US relations:
</P>
<P>
-- the two sides develop bilateral relations from a broader and
long-term point of view with the world situation in mind and the
21st century in perspective;
</P>
<P>
-- the two sides mutually take into account each other's
national conditions and respect each other's choice, tackle all
problems in bilateral relations in the spirit of friendship;
</P>
<P>
-- the two sides push bilateral economic cooperation toward an
all-round development by making full use of the advantages of the
two economies;
</P>
<P>
-- the two sides strengthen mutual consultation and cooperation
in international affairs and within international organizations;
</P>
<P>
-- the two sides increase exchanges between them, particularly
of high-level visits and contacts.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said at the meeting that a new constructive relationship
should and could be established between china and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1970s, Jiang said, leaders of China and the United
States re-opened the door for Sino-US relations. In the 20 years
that followed, bilateral relations grew smoothly in certain
periods while experienced difficulties and setbacks in other
periods. Historic experiences indicate that "we are able to do
things beneficial to the peoples of China and the United States
and the people in the world as a whole" when Sino-US relations are
handled properly, otherwise no party will benefit when such
relations get strained.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the world today is still turbulent and various
forces are being re-grouped. With the numerous complicated and
unstable factors, he said, China and the United States bear more
responsibility in maintaining world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that in this world of interdependence, economy has
become the first and foremost factor in relations between
countries, adding there are favorable conditions and a broad scope
for increased cooperation between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president noted that the Chinese government has
always attached importance to the relations with the United States
and hopes to be friendly with the United States. China will not
practice arms race, or join any military bloc, or seek military
expansion, or pose any threat to the security of the United
States. On the contrary, "we hope to increase mutual trust,
diminish troubles, promote cooperation and prevent confrontation"
with the United States, and to constantly promote Sino-US
relations on the basis of the three joint communiques between the
two countries. "We hope that the US government also pursue a
policy of friendship with China."
</P>
</TEXT>
