<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: President Jiang Zemin on Sino-US Relations (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In October 1995, Jiang and Clinton met for the third time when
they participated in the activities marking the 50th anniversary
of the United Nations in New York, under the background of Sino-US
relations suffering setbacks after the United States allowed
Taiwan's Lee Teng-hui to visit.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed that the issue of Taiwan is the most important
and sensitive one in Sino-US relations and is the core of the
three Sino-US joint communiques which constitute the foundation of
Sino-US relations. He said China does not want to see any incident
that would interfere with the smooth development of the bilateral
relations happen again.
</P>
<P>
"Our basic policy on Sino-US relations is: increase mutual
trust, diminish troubles, promote cooperation and prevent
confrontations. Our position is as follows:
</P>
<P>
"1. The leaders of the two countries should put bilateral
relations into a strategic perspective and strive to remove
various obstacles and interference so as to ensure that Sino-US
relations can constantly move forward in the correct direction;
</P>
<P>
"2. The three Sino-US joint communiques remain to be the
foundation of relations between the two countries. When the
communiques are observed, our bilateral relations will move
forward, and if not, there will be setbacks;
</P>
<P>
"3. It is common interest that has brought China and the
United States together. To promote and expand the common interest,
we should respect each other's national characteristics and
choice, surmount the gaps in social system and ideology, and
handle all issues between us in the spirit of equality,
consultation and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
During the APEC's informal leadership meeting in Manila in
1996, Jiang and Clinton, who was just re-elected US president, had
their fourth meeting, at which the two leaders decided to exchange
state visit in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that both the United States, the largest developed
country in the world, and China, the largest developing one, have
exerted great influence worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"Sino-US relations not only affect the fundamental interest of
the two peoples," the Chinese president said, "but inevitably
affect world peace, stability and development." Direct dialogues
between the heads of state of the two countries, Jiang added, will
be conducive to reducing or even wiping out differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
