<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges LTTE to Support Negotiated Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States has called
upon the rebel Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) to stop its
indiscriminate attacks and support a negotiated settlement of the
conflict in Sri Lanka, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government-owned Sunday Observer newspaper, in a belated
report of U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Karl Inderfuth's
speech in a House subcommittee on Wednesday, also said Washington
supports Colombo's constitutional reform plans in efforts to end
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"In Sri Lanka, where heavy fighting between government and LTTE
forces continues, the U.S. supports a negotiated political
settlement to the conflict," Inderfuth was quoted as saying in the
House International Relations Subcommittee on the Near East and
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The massive bomb attack in Sri Lanka's capital of Colombo on
October 15 only underlined the importance of ending the fighting,
the U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed belief that the Sri Lankan Government's
wide-ranging proposals for constitutional reform are a solid basis
for a peaceful solution to this tragic conflict, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U.S. government announced that the LTTE
is on its terrorist organization list and will be banned from
raising fund in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
One week after the announcement, a truck-bomb exploded in the
downtown business center of Colombo, killing 18 people and
injuring more than 100. Many landmark buildings in the area were
seriously damaged.
</P>
<P>
The attack was blamed on the LTTE, which has been fighting for
a separate state of its own in the north and east of the country
since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
