<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brokers See Opportunities in SOE Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese stock brokerage firms,
struggling in the crevice of keen competition, see a glimpse of
hope in the upcoming wave to restructure State-owned enterprises
(SOEs), today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Experts and officials believe that reshuffling property
ownership and management of SOEs offers opportunities for Chinese
stock companies, which are currently constrained by narrow
opportunities for development and deteriorating performance.
</P>
<P>
Stock firms' expertise in asset appraisal and transfer,
selecting acquisition objects, arranging mergers, sorting out
legal relations, distribution of employees and other aspects can
be helpful in SOE restructuring.
</P>
<P>
China has 97 stock brokerage companies, in addition to more
than 200 institutions involved in the business.
</P>
<P>
Underwriting and trading commissions are the major businesses
for most stock firms. But with the expansion of the stock market,
these firms are facing a hard time ahead.
</P>
<P>
Next year, the securities market is expected to see a glut of
supply as the country's quota of 30 billion yuan (3.6 billion
U.S. dollars) for A shares and 4.5 billion yuan (542 million
U.S. dollars) for convertible bonds will be enacted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Stock firms have lost profits from the difference of the issue
prices and trading prices by underwriting issues of stocks. They
can no longer survive by relying on their traditional business. So
they are rushing to shift their focus from traditional
underwriting to investment banking business.
</P>
<P>
The complex work and links in the SOEs' restructuring cannot be
done without the participation of stock firms, which have
experiences and skills in dealing with enterprise mergers.
</P>
<P>
In the past practice, enterprise restructuring was always
arranged by government "match-makers" instead of the market. Such
pairings usually lacked rational internal links.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, stock firms would create a broad market in which
all SOEs could find ideal co-operative partners and trade their
property.
</P>
<P>
Wang Liangzhong, an analyst from Guangfa Securities Co Ltd,
suggested that stock firms should establish stable co-operation
relationship with large enterprises, conglomerates and
well-performing firms.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the stock firms should extend underwriting
business in the distribution market to more in-depth services,
such as co-ordinating businesses' financial affairs, designing
asset structure and arranging business operations.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, stock firms should create new financing and
investment instruments to attract clients and promote efficiency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
