<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Imports Worsen Indonesia's Economic Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- High demand for imported goods,
especially during the recent currency crisis in Indonesia, has
contributed to a nation-wide economic slump, a cabinet minister
said.
</P>
<P>
"The total value of imports has been surpassing that of exports
for the past few years," Transmigration Minister Siswono
Yudohusodo said Saturday in Mataram, Indonesia's West Nusa
Tenggara province, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's non-oil and non-gas exports in 1996 amounted to
38.09 billion U.S. dollars, a significant increase from 34.95
billion dollars in 1995 and 30.33 billion dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesia's imports had also increased steadily to
39.33 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, compared with 37.71 billion
dollars in 1995 and 25.61 billion the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Siswono, who was former chairman of the Association of Junior
Indonesian Businessmen (HIPMI), said imports of big motorcycles
have been banned by the government except for sports, but they
still could be easily seen in Jakarta's traffic.
</P>
<P>
Luxury cars have also been imported into Indonesia, Siswono
said.
</P>
<P>
The over-demand for imported goods was expected to seriously
hit the economy, he said. He urged HIPMI members to buy and use
Indonesian-made products.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's current account deficit in 1996 was 8.8 billion
dollars, compared to 7 billion dollars in 1995 and 3.5 billion
dollars in 1994.
A sharp drop in Indonesia's current account would become a serious
problem for the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The key to the problem was to reduce imports and encourage
exports, although it would depend on the national and
international market situation, he said, adding that another
solution was to attract foreign investors to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, along with other currencies in Southeast
Asian, has been hit seriously by the monetary crisis since July
this year. The value of the rupiah has dropped by about 50 percent
against the U.S. dollar in the past 10 months.
</P>
<P>
Some economic analysts said Indonesia's economy is going
through its toughest time since the oil crisis in the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
