<HEADLINE> Top Companies Adopt Merger and Listing Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned trading
heavyweights are expected to unveil a massive merger plan and
listing schemes soon in a beefing-up campaign triggered by more
intense competition resulting from the country's trade
liberalization process.
</P>
<P>
China National Technology Import and Export Corp (CNTIC) and
three other leading trade companies have obtained preliminary
approval from the government to form a group company with a
combined annual trade volume of more than seven billion US
dollars, "Business Weekly" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The merger will involve China's seventh and 26th largest
traders -- China National Machinery Import-Export Corp and China
National Instrument Import and Export Corp.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the country's trade circles said Sinochem and the
China National Cereals, Oils and Foodstuff Import and Export Corp
are both preparing for domestic listings, while Sinochem also
plans a red chip offer in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The merger of the four companies aimed at the creation of a
supergroup to match international counterparts. The listed arms
will serve as effective instruments for the parent company's
fund-raising activities and promote financial engineering such as
mergers and acquisitions, the paper quoted China Securities
Co. analyst Tong Xuejun as saying.
</P>
<P>
Merger and business diversification, especially into
manufacturing, top the suggestions floated for the reorganization
of state-owned trading houses.
</P>
<P>
Insiders said many other state-trading firms are also
considering listing and the merger of these four may herald
similar moves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
