<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwatch Calls for Dismarmament of Small Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 25 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 million
military-style, hand-held weapons exist in the world now and the
uncontrolled spread of these weapons led to violence and
instabilities in regions and societies, said the Worldwatch in a
report released today.
</P>
<P>
Part of the weapons that individuals can carry provide massive
firepower for criminals, drug smugglers and part falls into the
hands of private armies and other civilians, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"These small arms are the tools for as much as 90 percent of
the killings in today's wars, and are the fuel of criminal
violence," noted researcher Michael Renner, author of the report.
</P>
<P>
The United States has by far the most small arms, the report
said, by one estimate enough to arm every adult and child in the
country. Firearm homicides in one day in the United States equal
that in one week in Europe and one year in Japan, it added.
</P>
<P>
Because of the spread of the small weapons, "disputes once
settled with words are now solved with hand grenades in El
Salvador. In Russia, South Africa and Angola, weapons meat for
war are now used by criminals to fuel crime waves and wage turf
battles," Renner said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that in Africa, elephant poachers use military
weapons to slaughter herds and intimidate guards at nature
preserves.
</P>
<P>
The report said that new arms production is one source of this
proliferation. Excess equipment from U.S., Russian and European
armies is routinely given away or sold cheaply to other countries.
Weapons left over after civil wars often enter the black market
and resurface at other hotspots, or find their way to drug cartels
and other organized crime groups.
</P>
<P>
"It may not be much of an exaggeration to say that we are
witnessing an era in which, in a sense, armies are disarming while
civilians are rearming," Renner said in the report.
</P>
<P>
In the United States alone, Renner said, the number of small
arms in circulation among the general population were officially
estimated at 192 million to 250 million.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended quick disarmament of combatants when
wars end, adoption of an international code on arms sales, a
clamp down on the illegal arms trade and destruction of collected
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971026.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Pledges to Promote Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBURGH, October 25 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting (CHGOM) issued the Edinburgh Economic
Declaration here this evening, calling on all Commonwealth
countries to promote cooperation on trade, investment and
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
This is the first economic declaration in the Commonwealth
history. The Commonwealth leaders devoted much attention at the
Edinburgh summit to the special theme: "Trade, Investment and
Development -- the Common Road to Commonwealth Prosperity."
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair told a press conference that
the Edinburgh economic declaration is "an exciting development" of
the 54-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
Under the declaration, the Commonwealth leaders have decided to
take following steps to remove trade barriers: establish a Trade
and Investment Facility, launch a Commonwealth action program to
remove administrative obstacles, promote Commonwealth Export
Training Centers, set up a Business Council made of major private
sector leaders from all regions of the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage investment flows, the declaration called
for the rapid finalization of Commonwealth Code for Good Practice
and establishment of a Commonwealth investment promotion program.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth leaders also expressed their concern at the
persistence of extreme poverty in many countries and the lack of
capacity to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the declaration pledged to work to halve the
proportion of people living in extreme poverty by the year 2015
and work towards a comprehensive solution of the debt problem.
</P>
<P>
On the worsening situation of world environment, the
Commonwealth decided to work with the international community "to
protect our planet for future generations".
</P>
<P>
The declaration also called for urgent action in the
international community to strengthen disaster relief response and
mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
